INSERT INTO `bookdetails` (`id`, `uid`, `title`, `descript`, `book`, `dateadd`, `applaud`, `censure`, `articleImage`) VALUES
(1, 'JasonChase', 'Dravieas Legend', 'The brother sister combination Take on the world full of mysteries and magic...', 'PROLOGUE\n"He will pay for what he has done. He cannot get away with it." Said the man who had hidden his face with a cloth tied around his ears.\r\nIt was moonlight night and there was plenty of light around, making it much harder for them to do what they were about to.\r\n"Are you sure you want to do this?" asked the woman who was crouched beside him. She had covered her face with a cloth just like her companion in a similar fashion, probably to cover themselves from the dust. There were in the middle of the desert after all and it was a windy night.\r\nThe location was very bizarre. Right in the middle of nowhere stood a very well guarded fort. No ruler would be foolish enough to stay in this hellish place. There was no sign of anything which could breathe around it, let alone subjects for him to rule. It was as if The Supreme himself didn\'t want this place habited. This place was meant for something else. And the way it was guarded, it was quiet clear that it was very important.\r\n"We have come a long way from that dreadful night. We cannot give up now. The way he betrayed us......all of us, that is what has been keeping me up at nights. I want revenge and I shall get it whether you like it or not." he said with a tone that his audience had never heard before.\r\n"Well, I better not let you die alone then." she said as she picked up her weapon. "Let\'s get the traitor."CHAPTER 1\n"You are going to have to do better than that, if you are to survive in the outside world." said Weyman Tauworth.\r\nWeyman Tauworth was a respected man in the village of Quencede. A master in the art of sword fighting and a well educated person. He was about forty to fifty years old but looked much younger. With dark brown shoulder length hair and sea green eyes, he looked handsome even. He had a well build body and musculature that depicted human\'s perfectness. He looked battle hardened even though he claimed to never have seen a battle in his life. A scar adorned his right arm, and how he got that still remains a mystery to the rest. There was something about him that attracted many towards him. His character was such that many  people often referred to him as \'a true noble, unlike those sitting on the throne in Sumterfell.\'  He usually helped the local government, govern Quencede. Not that it required much governing. The role of this governing body was just to settle some petty thievery or small land disputes. Things never exceeded this as the people of this village heard, happened everywhere else. Taking someone else\'s life was laughed at here, as a myth. Quencede\'s geographical as well as political position in the map was perfect. It lied on the southern end of the nation Laekenden, and away from its capital Sumterfell. It was also safe from the remaining two nations of Dravieas, Aldhetsern and Oasopern both of which were simply too far from this piece of land. Away from battles, wars, corruption and the politics, not even the Ruler of Laekenden seemed to care much about this place. Surrounded by mountain on one side, and the Barbaric Wilds on the other, with the Ocean of Laekenden lying far down south, it was almost cut off from the rest of Laekenden. It had only one route that allowed people to travel to Joretus, one of the major cities of Laekenden. But even that was quiet a distance away. As a result trade in Quencede was very meagre with traders arriving once in two or three years. But people here did not care. They were self dependent and did not crave for the spices from Aldhetsern or animal meat from Oasopern or fancy clothes from their own nation Laekenden. Simple people just making their living. It seemed as though corruption of mankind had not made its way here yet. Little did they know that it wouldn\'t take long for that to happen. \r\n"I  just got a little distracted, nothing to worry about father." said Rhaegon.  They were practising the art of sword fighting outside their small house. Rhaegon was Weyman\'s first child and his pride. Rhaegon boasted many of his father\'s features. The same dark brown hairs, sea green eyes and same skin tone. These features were something that characterised the Tauworth\'s. Although their grandfather was a little different but a little shuffling of characteristics wouldn\'t hurt anyone now, would it? Unlike his father, Rhaegon liked to keep his hair of the medium length, never letting it exceed his neck region. More hair meant, he had to spend more time on them, and he was lazy, he couldn\'t afford \'more time\'. Rhaegon\'s muscles were still in the developmental stage, but impressive already which had gotten many young ladies run after him . Above all, he was young and he had his entire life ahead of him, he was nineteen years old after all. The way his routine ran, and with his sword fighting training, it wouldn\'t take him much long to attain his father\'s status. He may be lazy, but when it came to swordsmanship, there was no compromise. He wanted to be the best and the strongest Swordsman ever to walk the lands of Dravieas. And that was what his father was training him to be.\r\n"In a real battle field, there will be fighting raging all around you, swords clashing, people cursing, screaming, dying. Now if you consider your lady friend here a distraction, then in a real battle you wouldn\'t last a minute." he pointed to Suzanne standing aside watching her best friend spar.\r\nSuzanne was a charmer, undoubtedly the most beautiful person Rhaegon had ever seen, which was just a handful bunch considering he had never seen ladies from outside Quencede, a village whose population did not exceed five thousand. Maybe an occasional merchant\'s daughter from Ulharter or Werpost or Joretus. But Suzanne was way better than them all. Suzanne had jet black, long hair. A round face with brown eyes and a perfect shaped nose. Everything about her was beautiful. It was no doubt that many young men lusted after her. But she didn\'t believe in a relationship before marriage. Suzanne and Rhaegon had known each other for almost their entire life. They knew everything about each other, be it a very dark secret or something that everyone knew. They understood and were very much comfortable around each other. There were many who believed that Rhaegon and Suzanne\'s relationship was something more than just best friends. But Rhaegon knew better. And so did Suzanne. Rhaegon respected Suzanne\'s motto of \'no relationship before marriage.\' Although people did freely talk about what a couple they would make and how their marriage will be a celebrated affair. Rhaegon did not mind any of that, in fact he had hoped that he would someday marry her. Suzanne on the other hand had never thought that far. She usually tended to ignore such things. But if she was to be married the very next day, then she knew that she wouldn\'t do it with anyone else other than Rhaegon. But for now they were best friends.\r\n"No, I was just passing by. I will leave now." She said hurriedly as she started walking away, obviously embarrassed. Rhaegon just looked at his feet, he was embarrassed as well. \r\n"I think this is enough for today. Go join her if you like." said his father with a smile on his face. Rhaegon looked up at his father, shocked.\r\n"Father its...not like-" his father cut him off with a raised hand.\r\n"It is okay son. Whatever you are going through.....it happens to the best of us." He almost mused the last part of his statement as if lost in thoughts.\r\n"Are you thinking about how you met mother?" Rhaegon pushed. After all he knew nothing about their history. How they met, or about their marriage, or even his mother\'s death. She had died when he was about six years old. His father had gone into depression for quite a while and even disappeared for some days. But he did return for his children. Rhaegon\'s younger sister, Aeliana who was three years old, was too young to understand the concept of death. She had always sat by the door waiting for her mother until she understood. Rhaegon had a vague image of her face, which was getting blurred every single day. And there was not a single time when he didn\'t probe his father to squeeze more information about her out of him.\r\n"Wait, I think I have changed my decision." joked Weyman.\r\nRhaegon knew that this chat about his mother would have to wait for another time. His father was a disciplined and serious man, and he only joked rarely. This was definitely one of his best days, and he didn\'t want to ruin it. Besides he was getting an early holiday.\r\n"Sorry father, I am going to go now." laughed Rhaegon as he hurried off after Suzanne.\r\n                                                      * * *\r\nRhaegon had to run quite a distance to catch up with Suzanne.\r\n"You are a fast walker." he said trying to catch his breath.\r\n"Or maybe I was just trying to get away from you." she said without looking at him.\r\n"Well that can\'t be true because if you wanted to, then you wouldn\'t be standing there watching me practise." She didn\'t reply to that. \r\n"Where are you heading to?" he asked.\r\n"Well, I got a bit of a free time so I thought I might just sit on the top of Cleavers hill and clear my mind." Cleavers was a small hill in Quencede, which could easily be climbed in about fifteen minutes. It was famous for its view of Quencede from its top. What with so many people going up there, it almost had, what looked like a natural road with trodden yellow leaves on it marking the way to the top.FDFD\n"You are going to have to do better than that, if you are to survive in the outside world." said Weyman Tauworth.\r\nWeyman Tauworth was a respected man in the village of Quencede. A master in the art of sword fighting and a well educated person. He was about forty to fifty years old but looked much younger. With dark brown shoulder length hair and sea green eyes, he looked handsome even. He had a well build body and musculature that depicted human\'s perfectness. He looked battle hardened even though he claimed to never have seen a battle in his life. A scar adorned his right arm, and how he got that still remains a mystery to the rest. There was something about him that attracted many towards him. His character was such that many  people often referred to him as \'a true noble, unlike those sitting on the throne in Sumterfell.\'  He usually helped the local government, govern Quencede. Not that it required much governing. The role of this governing body was just to settle some petty thievery or small land disputes. Things never exceeded this as the people of this village heard, happened everywhere else. Taking someone else\'s life was laughed at here, as a myth. Quencede\'s geographical as well as political position in the map was perfect. It lied on the southern end of the nation Laekenden, and away from its capital Sumterfell. It was also safe from the remaining two nations of Dravieas, Aldhetsern and Oasopern both of which were simply too far from this piece of land. Away from battles, wars, corruption and the politics, not even the Ruler of Laekenden seemed to care much about this place. Surrounded by mountain on one side, and the Barbaric Wilds on the other, with the Ocean of Laekenden lying far down south, it was almost cut off from the rest of Laekenden. It had only one route that allowed people to travel to Joretus, one of the major cities of Laekenden. But even that was quiet a distance away. As a result trade in Quencede was very meagre with traders arriving once in two or three years. But people here did not care. They were self dependent and did not crave for the spices from Aldhetsern or animal meat from Oasopern or fancy clothes from their own nation Laekenden. Simple people just making their living. It seemed as though corruption of mankind had not made its way here yet. Little did they know that it wouldn\'t take long for that to happen. \r\n"I  just got a little distracted, nothing to worry about father." said Rhaegon.  They were practising the art of sword fighting outside their small house. Rhaegon was Weyman\'s first child and his pride. Rhaegon boasted many of his father\'s features. The same dark brown hairs, sea green eyes and same skin tone. These features were something that characterised the Tauworth\'s. Although their grandfather was a little different but a little shuffling of characteristics wouldn\'t hurt anyone now, would it? Unlike his father, Rhaegon liked to keep his hair of the medium length, never letting it exceed his neck region. More hair meant, he had to spend more time on them, and he was lazy, he couldn\'t afford \'more time\'. Rhaegon\'s muscles were still in the developmental stage, but impressive already which had gotten many young ladies run after him . Above all, he was young and he had his entire life ahead of him, he was nineteen years old after all. The way his routine ran, and with his sword fighting training, it wouldn\'t take him much long to attain his father\'s status. He may be lazy, but when it came to swordsmanship, there was no compromise. He wanted to be the best and the strongest Swordsman ever to walk the lands of Dravieas. And that was what his father was training him to be.\r\n"In a real battle field, there will be fighting raging all around you, swords clashing, people cursing, screaming, dying. Now if you consider your lady friend here a distraction, then in a real battle you wouldn\'t last a minute." he pointed to Suzanne standing aside watching her best friend spar.\r\nSuzanne was a charmer, undoubtedly the most beautiful person Rhaegon had ever seen, which was just a handful bunch considering he had never seen ladies from outside Quencede, a village whose population did not exceed five thousand. Maybe an occasional merchant\'s daughter from Ulharter or Werpost or Joretus. But Suzanne was way better than them all. Suzanne had jet black, long hair. A round face with brown eyes and a perfect shaped nose. Everything about her was beautiful. It was no doubt that many young men lusted after her. But she didn\'t believe in a relationship before marriage. Suzanne and Rhaegon had known each other for almost their entire life. They knew everything about each other, be it a very dark secret or something that everyone knew. They understood and were very much comfortable around each other. There were many who believed that Rhaegon and Suzanne\'s relationship was something more than just best friends. But Rhaegon knew better. And so did Suzanne. Rhaegon respected Suzanne\'s motto of \'no relationship before marriage.\' Although people did freely talk about what a couple they would make and how their marriage will be a celebrated affair. Rhaegon did not mind any of that, in fact he had hoped that he would someday marry her. Suzanne on the other hand had never thought that far. She usually tended to ignore such things. But if she was to be married the very next day, then she knew that she wouldn\'t do it with anyone else other than Rhaegon. But for now they were best friends.\r\n"No, I was just passing by. I will leave now." She said hurriedly as she started walking away, obviously embarrassed. Rhaegon just looked at his feet, he was embarrassed as well. \r\n"I think this is enough for today. Go join her if you like." said his father with a smile on his face. Rhaegon looked up at his father, shocked.\r\n"Father its...not like-" his father cut him off with a raised hand.\r\n"It is okay son. Whatever you are going through.....it happens to the best of us." He almost mused the last part of his statement as if lost in thoughts.\r\n"Are you thinking about how you met mother?" Rhaegon pushed. After all he knew nothing about their history. How they met, or about their marriage, or even his mother\'s death. She had died when he was about six years old. His father had gone into depression for quite a while and even disappeared for some days. But he did return for his children. Rhaegon\'s younger sister, Aeliana who was three years old, was too young to understand the concept of death. She had always sat by the door waiting for her mother until she understood. Rhaegon had a vague image of her face, which was getting blurred every single day. And there was not a single time when he didn\'t probe his father to squeeze more information about her out of him.\r\n"Wait, I think I have changed my decision." joked Weyman.\r\nRhaegon knew that this chat about his mother would have to wait for another time. His father was a disciplined and serious man, and he only joked rarely. This was definitely one of his best days, and he didn\'t want to ruin it. Besides he was getting an early holiday.\r\n"Sorry father, I am going to go now." laughed Rhaegon as he hurried off after Suzanne.\r\n                                                      * * *\r\nRhaegon had to run quite a distance to catch up with Suzanne.\r\n"You are a fast walker." he said trying to catch his breath.\r\n"Or maybe I was just trying to get away from you." she said without looking at him.\r\n"Well that can\'t be true because if you wanted to, then you wouldn\'t be standing there watching me practise." She didn\'t reply to that. \r\n"Where are you heading to?" he asked.\r\n"Well, I got a bit of a free time so I thought I might just sit on the top of Cleavers hill and clear my mind." Cleavers was a small hill in Quencede, which could easily be climbed in about fifteen minutes. It was famous for its view of Quencede from its top. What with so many people going up there, it almost had, what looked like a natural road with trodden yellow leaves on it marking the way to the top.\nCHAPTER 2\n"Oh" Rhaegon said, disappointed. Normally when she said she needed to clear her mind, it meant she wanted to be alone.   \r\n"Would you care to join me?" she said, now looking at him. He didn\'t have to answer to that. He just walked beside her and they didn\'t talk until they had reached the top. There was something about her today that seemed new. She was sad, and was deep in thoughts. Rhaegon had sensed it but was just waiting for the right moment, when she would open up herself. \r\n"Nice look from up here, isn\'t it?" he said trying to calm her mood down as they stood on the edge. The entire Quencede, however small it was, was visible from here. The cluster of huts, houses, the market place with people bustling about the streets and a small portion of land on the farther side of the village where Shae - The Outcasts lived. The surrounding mountain chain and the wilds were visible in the distance. It was a breathtaking view that one would never get bored of. The sort, where you can just stand and watch for an entire day, without even feeling a muscle stretch. With all the greenery and the quiet and the peace, it escaped Rhaegon why some people left to stay in the capital Sumterfell. But then again he hadn\'t seen Sumterfell. \r\n"Yes." was all she said. He looked at her, concerned. She was in a deep trance. It was evident from the creases on her forehead and that distant look in her eyes, which didn\'t seem to look at anything in particular. Something was definitely wrong. He still chose not to ask it himself, with the fear that she might withdraw to herself.\r\n"So how is your quest to attain \'all the knowledge there is to attain\', coming along?" he said trying to make conversation. \r\n"It is coming along alright. The Preachers of the Couret seem to know everything. You shouldn\'t have left it you know. They are teaching all sorts of important things now, like why various things in the nature happen and the reasons behind them." she said with a sudden glee in her eyes. Talking about this always made her happy. \r\nCouret was like the Temple in the world of Dravieas. It was also the knowledge hub where all the young had to go until the age of 16 to attain basic knowledge. After that however it was the child\'s choice to whether continue or not. The Preachers were the priests who worshipped The Supreme and his Council of Gods. The Couret existed in every city, town and village no matter how remote it was or which nation it belonged to. Couret was welcome everywhere. It was the only religion in this world after all, one which was followed by everyone. \r\n"Nah, I am alright the way I am. I am a warrior you see. I don\'t want to learn all these stuff and then become a Preacher myself and then sit down and chant The Supreme\'s name all day. And besides I am learning all I can about battle strategies from my father and Ser Alexon. I should be alright. " he said.\r\nShe shook her head, "Continuing after the age of sixteen doesn\'t mean that you have to become a Preacher you know? You want to command the army of Laekenden one day, don\'t you? You can be at high places by my way too."\r\n"How is that?"\r\n"Well, you could be the Ruler\'s Advisor."\r\n"Ruler\'s Advisor?" he almost laughed out loud. "That doesn\'t involve any fighting. Commander of the Army is way much better. Is that what you are aiming for anyway? Becoming the Ruler\'s Advisor, and the second most powerful person in Laekenden?"\r\n"No way." she brushed the idea away with disgust. "That involves just too much politics than I can handle."\r\n"So what do you actually want to do? You never seemed to have shared that one."\r\n"Well....." her momentary glee seemed to have vanished as the sadness took their place back on her face.\r\n"Is there something wrong Suzanne?" he asked her finally. His attempt to make her mood light had only worked for a moment. Now he was concerned about her. He had never seen this kind of behaviour from her before. She looked at him, deep inside his eyes, deciding whether to reveal her secret or not. \r\nRhaegon watched into her eyes as tears were slowly filling in them like a flood in a village. He gave her a reassuring smile and laid his hand on her shoulder. And in an instant she made the decision. She could trust Rhaegon. She had to reveal this to someone and who better than to than her own best friend. In the few hours that she had learnt the secret, she was unable to think clearly. She had to get it out, which is why she had headed to Rhaegon\'s place instinctively, hoping to talk to him about what she had been told. Whether to believe it or not. \r\n"Rhaegon.......its" she broke down unable to control herself. He just pulled her close and hugged her, the way they always did when either of them was depressed.\r\n"Rhaegon....its.....wait, what is that?" she suddenly said in a shocked tone as she gently pulled away from his embrace. Rhaegon looked in the direction she was pointing at. It seemed as if a large sand storm was heading toward Quencede. It wasn\'t very far from the village.\r\n"What in the name of The Supreme is that?" he strained his eyes to see clearly. And that is when he realised that it was not a sand storm. It was just the sand displaced from the marching of a large number of people. It was an army battalion. \r\nAn army at Quencede was unthinkable. It didn\'t make sense. This wasn\'t a trade hub or near the borders to attract such interest. Unless the entire Laekenden had been defeated and the conquerors had come to claim their last prize at the edge of Dravieas, this was just insane. And even if that was the case, nobody would have needed an army to take on Quencede. There would be almost no resistance here, there were obviously no soldiers of Laekenden here, just some young fighters and that too their numbers not exceeding ten.   \r\n"It is not Laekenden." he said almost to himself.\r\n"What?" asked a startled Suzanne.\r\n"That is definitely not the army of Laekenden. Laekenden military wears blue coloured cloaks. So unless they have decided to change banners, that is not Laekenden." he explained. The unknown army was almost upon their village, when they got a clear look at them. About fifty men in Golden coloured armours, seemed to be marching towards their village. Although they had no weapons drawn or the stance of an army which was almost upon their prey, they were a fearful sight. \r\n"They are Gold Cloaks." said Suzanne, shocked.\r\n"The Order of Denkerst?" he asked, with certain amount of awe in his voice. "What could they be possibly doing in Quencede?" he asked. And in return she just gave him a concerned look.\r\n"This is not good." he said, "come on we have to warn the others." \r\n                                                       * * *         \r\n   "Are you sure they were Gold Cloaks?" asked his father, suddenly standing up from his chair. He was shocked to his bones. They were in his hut. Rhaegon and Suzanne had ran as fast as they could to warn the rest of them, and to raise some defence if it was even possible.\r\n"Yes, Ser Weyman. I myself saw it from atop Cleavers with Rhaegon. I have studied about the Order of Denkerst, that battalion\'s formation matches one of the most common Order\'s formation. And besides their armour style clearly says it all." Suzanne said who had recovered from the emotional breakdown she had just had. In this moment of crisis she had forgotten all about her secret and its possible implications. It had to wait for another time.\r\n"Well, let us not keep them waiting then." said Weyman as he picked up his sword which was kept on a rack.\r\n"Shouldn\'t we call on the others and try to defend it?" asked Rhaegon.\r\n"We should call on the others, but I don\'t think that this place needs defending at the moment." said his father calmly.\r\n"What do you mean?" Rhaegon was confused. He didn\'t care if it was the Gold Cloaks or a bunch of thieves, in his books, if a group of armed people are heading directly towards you, then it obviously meant trouble. It had failed him why his father didn\'t see it that way.\r\n"If what Suzanne said is true, if they really are the Golden Cloaks, then we have nothing to worry about. The Gold cloaks do not burn down cities. They do not exist to fight the humans. And they certainly do not have any political ambitions. And until they do we have nothing to worry about. Now, Suzanne go warn the other members of the local council. And Rhaegon you come with me, let us go welcome them." he commanded and Rhaegon knew that, this was the end of the discussion. Still he was uneasy, there was something that he felt was not right. Now this might be his intuition or him just being a little too pessimistic. Rhaegon picked up his sword as well and headed out the house after his father and Suzanne. \r\n"Take care Rhaegon." she said slowly after which she ran off in the other direction, towards the heart of the village. Meanwhile him and his father were heading towards the outer village, the part where the Shae lived. No doubt they would be panicking right now.\nCHAPTER 2\n<p>"Don\'t be scared, the worst that could happen is that we all get killed, warriors death and the rest who are alive get to serve the new masters." said Weyman with some amount of amusement in his voice. They were now walking with a brisk pace down the village lane. They could already hear the thumps of the battalion\'s marching.</p>\r\n<p>"What? I am not scared. I don\'t care what happens to me. I am just being cautious about what might happen." &nbsp;said a shocked Rhaegon. He couldn\'t believe that his father thought that he was scared. Whereas the truth was that, he wasn\'t feeling anything at all except adrenaline rushing into his blood and the surge of excitement. He wasn\'t scared at all. This worried him the most. Any person would have been shivering at their current prospect. It was just two of them going to meet a battalion of well trained soldiers. Even if what his father had told about the Gold Cloaks was true, it didn\'t mean that they were safe. If anything went wrong, it would mean that it would be just the two of them against around fifty battle hardened soldiers. And they didn\'t have any considerable backup too. Yet, with even these odds, he wasn\'t at all frightened.</p>\r\n<p>"I know. I was just joking." laughed his father. Rhaegon looked at him suspiciously. There was something seriously wrong here. His \'disciplined\' father was joking even at times like this?</p>\r\n<p>"What has happened to you?"</p>\r\n<p>"What? I am being a little optimistic here okay? And it feels good, you should try it sometimes." smiled his father, only to be returned by his son\'s glare. "Come on, you don\'t really think they are going to attack Quencede do you? They are Gold Cloaks and they keep track of each and every place. They would know that we have no defence and yet they would still bring a battalion? I don\'t think so. I believe that whatever is going to happen, it will be for our own good."</p>\r\n<p>Rhaegon realised that whatever his father was saying, was actually making sense. He smiled at his father.</p>\r\n<p>"Look, I know that you feel, none of this is right. And you are correct at your place to some extent. We will take on whatever is coming, together. Relax a little." said his father. Rhaegon nodded his assent.</p>\r\n<p>They had arrived at the village\'s outer part. The Shae\'s were definitely getting restless as they looked as if they were ready to burst into the inner village. There were men arguing about reasons unknown but the women and children did their best to stay in the shadow and keep their mouths shut. The golden army was visible at a distance now, lead by a single person on horseback, valiantly riding at a slow pace so that his foot soldiers behind him could keep up.</p>\r\n<p>Ser Alexon had already arrived at the scene before Rhaegon and his father. He was just standing there with a sheathed sword strapped to his waist, watching the golden army arrive, whilst completely ignoring the shouting Shae\'s all around him. He was a different person. A war veteran and the former commander of a Laekenden battalion. And his battalion was one among many that fought against the Duncan Stormwell\'s army and he had a major role in defeating Stormwell and putting Galer Redmere at the throne of Laekenden. However, he was injured considerably, with his left arm paralysed, during the war and he quit shortly after, seeing that he could not serve the throne the way he previously did. However many people said that, he had seen many horrors in that war that he could take it no more and he receded to this outlandish place for his retirement. His father and Ser Alexon were friends since then. Ser Alexon might have a paralysed hand but he was still a fearful sight in a direct combat. His physique was built for war. He had a major role in Rhaegon\'s sword fighting training.</p>\r\n<p>"Welcome to the party, Weyman." Ser Alexon said as he saw them arrive.</p>\r\n<p>"We should probably ask the Shae\'s to leave. They will only make things worse." said Weyman. Ser Alexon just nodded in return. He was just as moody as Rhaegon\'s father was.</p>\r\n<p>Weyman turned around and shouted as loud as he possibly could, addressing the hundreds of Shaes there. "Listen everyone, the women and the children are allowed to enter Quencede until further decision is made. You can ask for the villagers to give you shelter and I am sure that they will be more than willing to help at times like this. The men however are advised to go back to their huts as we cannot accommodate everyone. You are to await further announcements. In case things get out of hand, run into the village and save your family and in the process, if possible try and help others."</p>\r\n<p>After the announcement, some gave out wails of disappointment while others, bid their good byes to their children and wives and prepared to head into village. The entire community burst into action, getting ready to do whatever it was that they were advised to do.</p>\r\n<p>The code of Dravieas had termed the low borns as \'The Shae\'. They were never allowed to enter any village or city or anything without any purpose. Purpose being, work. It was these people after all who were the labour force. They did everything from cleaning houses to cook to labour in building massive structures under the supervision of a high born. The only place they were allowed to however was ironically, the Couret. The Couret\'s were usually located at the heart of the cities and villages, which made the Shaes not to go there as well. These poor souls stayed in camps outside cities and villages. They would get their supplies from the governing body separately at a slight higher cost. Rhaegon hated it all. He had never understood the concept of \'low borns and high borns\'. When questioned, some would say to leave things as they are and some would look down upon him as if he had done a crime. His father however agreed with him, but not to an extreme extent. He commanded much respect in this village, yet he had never publicly raised this subject. But he knew that, his father couldn\'t achieve anything in this prospect. This was a practise that was going on since time immemorial and was followed everywhere in Dravieas. It would take more than just one man to bring about a change. If it was in Rhaegon\'s power, he would declare every Low born to be a high born and thus abolish the practise. Sadly, he knew that this was not going to be true, at least in the present scenario.</p>\r\n<p>"The Council won\'t like that." said Ser Alexon, still looking straight at the marching army.</p>\r\n<p>"I know. To hell with the Council. They really won\'t care about where the Shae\'s are at times like this." he said little angrily.</p>\r\n<p>"You really don\'t know them then." he said, now turning to look straight into Weyman\'s eyes. "They do not look down upon the Shae\'s as softy as we do. What do you say Rhaegon?"</p>\r\n<p>"Well.....I was about to ask, why you didn\'t let the men enter too. I mean they will be more safer inside the village even if they are sitting on roads." he said little hesitantly.</p>\r\n<p>This statement brought smiles onto both old men\'s faces.</p>\r\n<p>"Like father like son I believe." chuckled Ser Alexon.</p>\r\n<p>"Hurry up people." commanded Weyman as the army had almost arrived.</p>\r\n<p>Rhaegon, his father and Ser Alexon stood together facing the army. Strangely, he was the only one, having his hand on the hilt. The Golden army had come to halt right in front of them. Rhaegon looked behind him, the entire Shae\'s camp had gone silent. The women and children had already made their way into the village. Most of the men were inside their huts, with some curious eyes peering from the windows and some brave men watching right from the outside. He turned to face the guests. All he saw was beaten and bloodied soldiers, led by a burly man sitting on a horse. They were Gold Cloaks alright. It was crystal clear now that he could see them all up close.</p>\r\n<p>"Greetings!" said the man on the horse, bending his back a little, a gesture of respect. His voice was very coarse and heavy.</p>\r\n<p>"Greetings to you too, commander!" his father greeted back.</p>\r\n<p>The commander looked behind them and realised what had happened. "Oh, you didn\'t think we were invaders now, did you?" he smiled.</p>\r\n<p>"What is the Order doing here?" asked Ser Alexon suspiciously. The commander looked quiet shocked with Ser Alexon\'s tone.</p>\r\n<p>"So right to the point, huh?" he said as he climbed down from his horse, and quickly a soldier ran forward to hold its reins. The commander was a tall man even when he was not on the horse. "No matter. We are the Order of Denkerst." he took off his helmet, revealing a crooked and scared face. He had a bloodshot eyes and a scar running through his nose, and his lips were as thin as a thread. An ugly man to be honest. "And I am Darius, the commander of 3rd battalion of the Order." he said proudly.</p>\r\n<p>"And I am Alexon, former Commander of a Laekenden battalion."</p>\r\n<p>"Oh! That explains." he smiled.</p>\r\n<p>"So what do we owe this pleasure?" asked Rhaegon\'s father.</p>\r\n<p>Darius hesitated for a moment before he spoke. "Umm..... we are in the middle of a mission, assigned to us by the Welminer himself. And we are looking to camp here to rest and refill our supplies, before we head out to our final destination."</p>\r\n<p>By now, the governing body of the village had arrived. All elderly people looking worried and a little angry, probably because of the little Shae matter. All the Shaes that were in the camp, came out to watch the whole scene as they realised that there was going to be no bloodshed and that they were all safe.</p>\r\n<p>"But that doesn\'t explain the blood."&nbsp; Rhaegon said. He had observed the blood that was on all of their armours.</p>\r\n<p>"Excuse me?" asked a shocked Darius.</p>\r\n<p>All eyes were boring into Rhaegon now. "The blood stains on your armour," he said pointing at their them, "They look fresh. Probably two or three days old. So who did you have to fight on your way here?"</p>\r\n<p>"Sorry, who are you again?" said the commander as he made an absent minded attempt to wipe his cloak clean.</p>\r\n<p>"Rhaegon Tauworth."</p>\r\n<p>"See Rhaegon, these blood stains are not of a human being as you might suspect. These are some of the wild wolves that we have had to encounter in the wilds."</p>\r\n<p>"With all due respect Commander, how many men did you actually set out with?" he asked.</p>\r\n<p>"What do you mean by that?" asked back the commander, now getting a little annoyed.</p>\r\n<p>"Your battalion here houses thirty three men, give or take a few. Nobody takes such a odd number into any mission. So unless, you lost a few men along the way, which would be impossible if wild wolves were the only things that you faced, it doesn\'t make sense. So would you care to explain, what actually happened?" This whole thing was very suspicious to him. He didn\'t believe a single word the commander said. Something was definitely wrong here.</p>\r\n<p>"Careful there child." said an angered Darius.</p>\r\n<p>"Enough!" said the village leader. "All they want to do is camp here right? I can see no harm in this. Commander Darius, you can have your men camp here and you are welcome to my house as a guest."</p>\r\n<p>"But-" Rhaegon\'s protest was cut short by, the village leader.</p>\r\n<p>"I appreciate your readiness to act son, but I think we got things in control here."</p>\r\n<p>Rhaegon pulled back after this. It seemed nobody was seeing this the way he was seeing it. There was nothing he could do now except watch Darius\' smug smile, as he pushed through him to make his way to the village headman\'s house.</p>\r\n<p>"Camp here! Raise tents. Provisions will be taken care of shortly." announced Darius. After which he headed into the village to the leader\'s house. The crowd slowly began dissipating.</p>\r\n<p>"Nice work there." appreciated Ser Alexon, as soon as they were alone. &nbsp;"It takes courage to speak up like that and that too, to such an audience."</p>\r\n<p>"Thanks, Ser." he smiled.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;"There is this feeling that I have......that something is not right." Rhaegon continued.</p>\r\n<p>"You are right, Rhaegon. We have got to keep our eyes open." he replied as he too headed off into the village.</p>\r\n<p>"Come on, we have got work to do." said Weyman as he directed his son to follow him into the village. "As much as you may argue, we have to send the Shaes back or else the council would burn me alive." They both laughed.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * * *</p>\nChapter 2\n<p>"Fetch that huntress of a sister of yours." said Weyman. He was<br />sitting in his house drinking leeade, an alcoholic drink very much<br />famous in Dravieas. "I don\'t know what she does in the Barbaric<br />Wilds all day with that bow and arrows. Things are complicated here<br />as it is. And I don\'t want her to be alone out there, what with so<br />many soldiers roaming about."<br />"Right away, Father." Rhaegon nodded.<br />* * *<br />Rhaegon was making his way through the Barbaric Wilds, just a short<br />distance from Quencede. Barbaric Wilds was this dense forest<br />stretch, with trees whose length never seemed to end. It was almost<br />impossible to see the sky from down below here. Barbaric wilds was<br />fabled to house many monsters, dangerous creatures and even<br />Grimmoths. This was just a myth as nobody had seen anything in<br />years. And also one had to go deep inside to see things and nobody<br />had dared trespass here, given the dangerous outlook of the scene.<br />But, the outer parts of these wilds was not so dense or dangerous.<br />His sister, Aeliana often came out here to practise her archery and<br />she was surprisingly brilliant in it. She could even close her eyes and<br />still hit the target, a credit to her hearing capabilities. She was<br />mentored by a man in mid fifties named Greg, a local hunter,<br />although she had long surpassed him in the skill of archery.<br />It was getting almost dark and he had to get to her fast. There was a<br />clearing in these wilds, where she normally used to practise all day. It<br />would be only moments before it became completely dark and he<br />preferred to not roam these wilds when it was.<br />He cut down the overgrown foliage that was blocking his way to the<br />clearing, with his sword. He stepped into the small clearing, only to<br />find it empty. This clearing formed a small circle, so perfect it almost<br />looked manmade. There were some clay idols with holes pierced into<br />their faces, to an extent that they looked scary. His sister practised<br />here alright. And besides he knew this was the place, because he was<br />here twice before under similar circumstances. There was no sign of<br />her now. She could not have already left for Quencede, cause if she<br />had he would have seen her on the way. The path that he had taken<br />to reach here was the only safest way to reach this place. And<br />besides, it was the route that Aeliana always took. But then again his<br />sister was always unpredictable, so it wouldn\'t be surprising if she<br />had taken another route. This worried him deeply.<br />There was sudden rustling of leaves, behind him. Rhaegon carefully<br />drew his sword and turned in that direction. There was definitely<br />someone there. His guess was some petty thieves. There were some<br />gangs of thieves hiding out here, in these wilds, waiting to prey on<br />deserters. He had heard many stories about them from Aeliana<br />herself. He slowly started to walk towards the place from where the<br />sound had come. It was completely dark now, and it was almost<br />impossible to see anything. Another rustle, and then he heard a<br />familiar sound.<br />SWOOSH!<br />He saw it in the last moment, an arrow aimed straight at his head. He<br />dodged it at the last moment, but he could feel it whiz past his ears.<br />His heart was racing now, it was really difficult to fight an archer with<br />a sword in such a bad light condition. But somewhere at the back of<br />mind he knew that, this archer was his sister.<br />"Hahaha!" Sure enough Aeliana laughed, proving his doubts right.<br />She came out of the foliage and into the clearing. With her was Greg.<br />She was still laughing.<br />"Are you crazy? You could have killed me!" Rhaegon shouted. He was<br />angry but he was also really relieved to see his sister safe.<br />"Aww....come on, even you know, that arrow would never have hit<br />you. It was a calculated shot. Calculated to only whiz past you and do<br />nothing more. I would have loved to see the reaction on your face,<br />but curse the timing, I could see nothing."<br />Rhaegon smiled. This was just typical of Aeliana. She was beautiful.<br />She was no different from the other Tauworth\'s. She had the same<br />dark brown coloured hair that went on till her hips. The same dark<br />green eyes that he had. But she looked more beautiful than him.<br />Their father had always said that she had inherited her mother\'s<br />looks. Rhaegon loved his sister very much. Probably because she<br />reminded him about their mother. They shared a very special bond.<br />He was sometimes over protective about her and rightly so. When<br />their mother had passed away, Aeliana was so vulnerable and alone.<br />It was then that he had taken an unspoken oath that he would never<br />let anything happen to her, ever. And Aeliana, loved her brother back<br />with the exact same amount. Probably even more. She was proud of<br />him. She would always listen to him. There was no sibling rivalry<br />between them. She respected him too. After all it was him that had<br />stood by her, when she had said that she wanted to be an archer. A<br />lady learning battling skills, was looked down upon in Dravieas. Her<br />father was against this as well, but it was her warrior brother that<br />had convinced him to let her learn archery. She would follow him<br />everywhere. Be it battle or death, she knew she would be there for<br />him, just like she knew of her brother\'s oath.<br />"What were you doing there anyway?" he asked.<br />"Well, we heard someone coming, but we were not sure who it was.<br />So we just hid there in case it was a thief."<br />"And then you shot an arrow at me." he smiled.<br />"Once, I knew it was you," she placed her hand on his shoulder, "I<br />thought maybe lets scare your guts out." she winked.<br />"I indicated her not to. But you know her, she wouldn\'t listen." said<br />Greg.<br />"It is okay. I am kind of used to her pranks now." he smiled. "Come<br />on we should be heading back now. Father would be worried."<br />"Miss your sister much?" she asked him, once they were making<br />their way through the wilds.<br />"What?"<br />"You came to personally escort me, now that doesn\'t happen<br />everyday. So did you miss me?" she winked. She always joked about<br />all things. Never serious about anything until absolutely necessary.<br />This attitude of hers is what made her so adorable.<br />"Ooooh....don\'t you think that you are that important okay. The Gold<br />Cloaks are here in Quencede, so father asked me to bring you back.<br />That is all, no missing you and all." he laughed.<br />"Oh." she faked disappointment.<br />"Come on, you are so bad at faking, even you know that."<br />"But it wouldn\'t hurt for you to say that, you missed me a little,<br />would it?" she looked at him.<br />"I suppose not." She kept looking at him, as if expecting to hear<br />more. "What? I am not going to say it." he laughed.<br />"Wait a moment here guys. Did you just say that, The Gold Cloaks are<br />here?" asked Greg, who was in his own thoughts until now.<br />"Yes." he answered. And suddenly his anxiety returned back.<br />"The Gold Cloaks as in The Order of Denkerst?" Greg raised his<br />eyebrows.<br />"Yes." he answered again.<br />"This is new. What do they want?" he enquired.<br />"You\'ll see." Rhaegon muttered.<br />* * *<br />"You will never taste a better leeade, in the entire south,<br />commander." said the village leader, as he poured two glasses of the<br />drink.<br />"I don\'t doubt that for a second. I thank you for taking us in. The<br />Order will remember." said Darius as he accepted the drink.<br />"Quencede has always given refuge to the, wandering migrates.<br />Some of whom have lost their way, or some who just want to<br />explore. I saw you people as no different. You were in the need of<br />help, and that is what we offered. But I do truly apologise on behalf<br />of that kid. He shouldn\'t have interrogated you like that."<br />"You don\'t have to. That kid is right in his place. I am sure he has his<br />reasons for his behaviour. Though his observational skills were quiet<br />impressive." said Darius as he slowly sipped on the drink. "Who is he<br />by the way?"<br />"His name is Rhaegon Tauworth, son of Weyman Tauworth, the<br />advisor to the council here."<br />"I see. He looks trained." he said.<br />"He is. He is the best swordsman of his age I have ever seen. Trained<br />by his father and a former Commander. He is pretty impressive with<br />a sword." he nodded.<br />"He is The Order material." Darius mused.<br />"Are you saying, what I think you are saying?"<br />"You know it. His talents will be wasted if he stays here. There is no<br />job for people like him or me in this side of Dravieas."<br />"But I don\'t think, he wants to join The Order. He has other plans."<br />"That\'s what they all say. That is what I said in the beginning. But<br />once an opportunity is handed, nobody seems to put it down. The<br />brave ones I mean. Fighting Grimmoths for a living isn\'t easy, but it<br />sure as hell is fun." he laughed.<br />"So, umm..... Grimmoths,....., you\'ve seen them recently?" he<br />enquired, although he knew the odds of getting that question<br />answered was none.<br />Darius hesitated for a moment, thinking about how best to answer<br />the question. "I won\'t lie to you my friend, but the truth is this.<br />Grimmoths are a rare species now. Whatever is left of their breed<br />are in hiding, and we have no idea where."<br />"Well that\'s part good news." he laughed as he raised his glass in<br />celebration. "So, casually asking, what happens to the Order when<br />the Grimmoths are finally extinct?"<br />"I don\'t know. We might just change our laws and find us a new<br />purpose." he laughed.<br />"Indeed." he laughed with his guest. "But I bet whatever this new<br />purpose you guys will invent, it will never be as good as Grimmoths.<br />They are like the most meanest creatures in the whole of Dravieas, a<br />perfect villain for you guys to become the heroes."<br />"I will let you in on a secret, my friend. The darkness never goes<br />away. You take one bad guy out, there are two more behind him, to<br />make him look as if he was a kid." he mused.<br />"Aren\'t you in philosophical mood today?" the leader joked.<br />"The leeade gets the best out of me." Darius smiled.<br />"It gets the best out of everyone." he mused. And suddenly there<br />was banging on the door. Someone wanted to get in frantically. "Let<br />me better get that before he breaks through it." Darius just raised his<br />glass in the return. There was a Gold Cloak standing when the leader<br />opened the door, and he looked like he had eaten something<br />indigestible and had to throw it out of his system.<br />"I have to speak with Commander Darius." he said.<br />"Don\'t bother yourself, let me get that.", said Darius as he sipped up<br />the rest of his drink and headed towards the door. "Forgive me<br />friend. I\'ll be back before you know it." he said as he headed out of<br />the house, closing the door behind him.<br />The leader shrugged, as he headed back and picked up the glasses<br />from the table to take them to the kitchen. Just then he saw, Darius\'<br />things wrapped up in a cloth, kept in the corner of the room they<br />were just sitting in. He knew that he shouldn\'t mess with it, but his<br />curiosity got the better of him. He wanted to know what a<br />commander would carry into the battle. He looked at the door which<br />he had bolted from the inside, so there was no way the commander<br />would figure his act out, unless he messed with his too much, which<br />he decided that he will not and that he will just take a sneak peak. He<br />untied the cloth that was covering his stuff, and what he saw inside<br />blew his mind away.<br />What was inside, was no ordinary thing. He saw an oval shaped, a<br />slight green coloured object, with a scaly exterior. It was slightly big<br />in size. First he didn\'t understand what it was, but slowly the reality<br />set in. He recognised the scales on the object. It was an egg. And no<br />ordinary egg for that matter. It was a Grimmoth egg. It was very rare,<br />making him one of the very few men to ever have seen it. Rhaegon<br />was right after all, he realised. Now he understood everything, the<br />blood on them, their strange numbers. Their mission was to steal a<br />Grimmoth egg. He began panicking, as he realised the consequences.<br />Grimmoths were very protective of their own kind, which meant that<br />a Grimmoth was searching for the thing he was looking at right now.<br />The Order was being hunted by this Grimmoth, and they were on the<br />run, and they had just jeopardised entire Quencede. The harsh<br />realisation set the man in action as he picked up the egg, which was<br />surprisingly light for its weight, and ran out of his house to his<br />advisor.<br />* * *<br />"Holy shit!" cursed Weyman, as he saw what the village leader was<br />holding in his hands. "He should have told us before."<br />"He didn\'t, because he knew that if he did, we would never help<br />them. We need to act fast."<br />"He has brought an apocalypse on us. Evacuate the goddamn city.<br />Take every single person and don\'t leave anyone behind, not even<br />the Shaes."<br />"But where do I take them?" asked a panicked leader.<br />"Anywhere. Take them to Barbaric wilds for all I care. Just take them<br />away from here." the leader nodded and turned to leave. "And one<br />more thing, leave the egg here. That creature is coming for it, and it<br />can sense it."<br />"What are you going to do? Will you not come with us?" he asked<br />emotionally.<br />"Have my children come back?"<br />"I don\'t think so. But they are not here, so they will be safe. We will<br />meet them on our way, Weyman."<br />"I have lived longer than I should, Jeff." he said slowly, calling the<br />leader by his name, something which he had never done before.<br />"Find them and tell them that Camille and I loved them, okay?"<br />Jeff nodded in return and turned to leave when he heard the blood<br />curling cry of a Grimmoth. A screech that made one cover his ears<br />and crawl back under the bed, never to come out. It sent chills<br />through the body of each and every person who heard it. And every<br />single person in and around Quencede did. The Gold cloaks obviously<br />knew what was upon them, so they weren\'t as much astonished as<br />the villagers did. Every human of this generation, had only heard of<br />the Grimmoths, never had seen them. Some considered it a myth of<br />the past. Only the Gold Cloaks had claimed to have seen them in the<br />recent times.<br />It was not long before they all heard the flaps. The flaps of its wings,<br />and it sounded just as terrifying.<br />"Get out of here Jeff, fast." Weyman said in a panicked tone. But it<br />was too late. There was another big Grimmoth shout, this time it was<br />very close, and a few moments later, Weyman could feel nothing but<br />light and heat around him as his life was slowly sucked out of him.<br />* * *<br />They all heard the blood curling cry come from afar. They were shell<br />shocked. Rhaegon just stood there, not believing what he had just<br />heard. Because if he did, he could not cope up with what it meant to<br />his townsmen and more importantly to him, his father and Suzanne.<br />"Was that.....a Grimmo-" Aeliana was about to say, but was cut short<br />by Rhaegon.<br />"No! Don\'t just jump to conclusions, okay. We need to move fast<br />there, and see what it is for ourselves." he was panicking now. He<br />very well knew what it was.<br />"Go there and see for ourselves? Do you even hear yourself? We<br />both know what that is. And you still want to go there, right into<br />hell?" Greg demanded.<br />\'Yeah, well what do you propose, Greg? We stand here and enjoy the<br />sight?" he shouted.<br />"I am saying, we can save our lives now before it is too late."<br />"And what about, our family in there, Greg? Oh wait a second, you<br />don\'t have one, which perfectly explains your behaviour." he<br />thundered.<br />"Think for a moment, Rhaegon. Do you really want to take your sister<br />to that place now?" he said somewhat backing off.<br />Rhaegon looked at Aeliana. She had tears in her eyes, but was trying<br />very hard to let them not show. He knew that she was not afraid of<br />the creature out there, but for all the other people down below. He<br />realised his mistake, he shouldn\'t be taking her to that place after all,<br />because he knew that Quencede would no longer exist by the time<br />he got there.<br />"You are right." he nodded, holding back tears himself. "Take her,<br />and get away from here, as far as possible. Head to Joretus, and wait<br />for me there, if I don\'t catch up with you."<br />"No. I am not going anywhere, without you and father." she said<br />stubbornly.<br />"Aeliana, we don\'t have time for this okay. You need to stay safe. Go<br />with Greg, I will meet you later. In the meantime I will have to see if I<br />can help any survivors." he said with a heavy heart.<br />"Our father is there, Rhae. I want to see him as much as you do<br />okay? So I don\'t care whether you want to keep me safe or not, but I<br />am going there with or without you. So you choose between the two<br />of them." she said angrily.<br />"But Aeliana that might be a Grimmoth. That will make survival<br />almost impossible, and I don\'t want to lose you too."<br />"Does it matter? You just said survival is impossible, so you go there,<br />and suppose you don\'t survive, then how will it matter to you<br />whether I did or not?"<br />"Okay. I am going to ignore you just said that. Greg time for you both<br />to leave." he decided.<br />"You know what indication you just gave me Rhaegon? You told me<br />that father is probably dead, and you are going to the battlefield to<br />die and you are leaving me out in the dry, all alone. You want that<br />kind of life for me?"<br />"I want life for you, sister." he screamed with anger. He couldn\'t<br />believe he was hearing such words from her.<br />"Well, I don\'t want that kind of life for myself, okay?" she cried. He<br />sighed as he gave in. He hadn\'t seen his sister like this before, but<br />given the circumstances, anyone could lose their minds. He knew<br />that his sister could be very stubborn at times, and that they were<br />wasting precious time, arguing.<br />"Fine, but you are going to stay close to me, and be careful."<br />"Don\'t I always?" she showed a faint smile, wiping the tears from her<br />cheek.<br />"Well, let\'s hurry then." said Greg then as he turned to leave.<br />"What changed your mind?" Rhaegon asked as they began their<br />sprint towards the village.<br />"She did."<br />* * *<br />There was fire everywhere. Huts, houses, corpses, everything was<br />burning, with a blazing red, hot fire. Rhaegon, Greg and Aeliana came<br />to a sudden stop. Their fears were just proven right. There was no<br />movement at all, from anywhere except for, pieces of buildings<br />falling down to the ground. From the look of it, no survivors. There<br />was no sign of the Grimmoth that caused this either. Not that<br />Rhaegon gave a damn about that now. He slowly walked through the<br />ruins of his own village which was just a few moments ago, bustling<br />with people, but now just a blazing inferno. He didn\'t want to believe<br />what he was seeing. He badly hoped that all this was just too bad to<br />be true. I mean, it\'s not every day that, a creature which hasn\'t been<br />seen by common people in centuries, just happen to show up , and<br />destroy your village. He had just hoped that it was all just a dream<br />and he would wake up any time now with a start. His thoughts now<br />shifted to his friends, his father, Suzanne. He made place for a little<br />hope inside his throbbing heart.<br />Maybe they might have made it out. Maybe they got the warning<br />and they made it out of the village! He thought. But somewhere at<br />the back of his mind, he knew that his father, and Suzanne would<br />never run away from this place while there were still people here.<br />But little hope that they might have was the only thing that was<br />keeping him up right now. He had never imagined his life without<br />them, and he wasn\'t ready to imagine it now. He looked at his sister.<br />Her condition was worse. He knew what was going through her right<br />now. Witnessing a massacre at such a tender age, will without a<br />doubt shake you up. But he had to worry about her later. Now he<br />had to look for survivors.<br />"Greg, look for anyone who might need help! I am going to search for<br />my father." he choked on his own voice, but Greg got the message.<br />He nodded grimly, although he knew that it was just three living<br />souls in that place at the moment.<br />"Aeliana stay here, okay?" he said slowly.<br />She just looked into the distance and only uttered one word-"Father"<br />"He will be alright, okay. Don\'t worry. Just stay here, and I will go get<br />him." he assured her with a heavy heart. She just nodded. Rhaegon,<br />held her arm and took her to a place away from the fire and then sat<br />her down. He nodded to her and then ran to the place where his<br />house used to be.<br />Greg meanwhile was searching through the debris for anyone who<br />was still alive. He walked through the entire village without any luck,<br />and reached the area where the Shaes lived. Nobody here was<br />breathing either. All of their huts burning with their owners inside<br />them. He couldn\'t handle it no more. He was sick by looking at all the<br />deaths. Death by fire, one of the most painful ways of dying.<br />Somewhere at the back of his mind, he felt relieved that he hadn\'t<br />allowed Aeliana to go back home early, when she had asked him to.<br />He couldn\'t bear to think of her, being a part of this massacre. But<br />still, there were other small children here, innocent people who died<br />for no reason at all. People who didn\'t deserve to die such a brutal<br />death. He looked around him. There really were no survivors at all.<br />And yet he suddenly noticed something strange. There were, large<br />number of footsteps, heading away from the village. And also, there<br />were holes driven into the ground, a clear indication that tents had<br />been set up here recently. He remembered Rhaegon telling him that,<br />The Order of Denkerst were here. That explained the, holes. They<br />had camped here. But there were no tents at the moments, and they<br />clearly hadn\'t burned down because there was no sign of their<br />debris. And the large number of footsteps heading away from the<br />village, must be the theirs. They must have packed up and left<br />before the attacked occurred. But that didn\'t make any sense,<br />because they had only arrived hours ago, and nobody would be<br />foolish enough to camp for just a couple of hours. And above all, the<br />job of the Gold Cloaks was to oppose the Grimmoths, and if this<br />really was a Grimmoth attack, then why did they run away? This was<br />not right. Something was fishy.<br />* * *<br />Rhaegon ducked the blazing fire as he slowly made his way into<br />what used to be his house. There was light and fire everywhere. It<br />was too hot, and he was sweating profusely, but not all of it was due<br />to heat. He looked around frantically around for his father.<br />"FATHER! CAN YOU HEAR ME?" he shouted over the sound of<br />burning wood. He didn\'t hear any reply. He suddenly felt as if he<br />stepped over something, and he looked down to see, a burned body.<br />Tears filled his eyes as he bent down to take a clear look. He<br />suddenly felt a momentary gush of relief as he realised that it was<br />not his father but the village leader, Jeff.<br />This momentary relief didn\'t last long as he looked right next to Jeff\'s<br />corpse to see the one thing he wished he never would have to see.<br />His father\'s charred body lay there, barely recognisable. But he knew<br />it was him. The feeling in burning heart said it all. He looked at his<br />father\'s face, which was contorted, in an expression of shock, that<br />was recorded by the fire for time immemorial.<br />What kind of brutal creature would do this?, he thought. Tears rolled<br />down his cheeks, as he could control it no more. He had always<br />known his father to be a brave and understanding person. But now<br />looking at him lying like this, burnt to the bone, made him sick.<br />This couldn\'t be true, he thought, This is a bad dream. Supreme<br />would never allow something like this to happen.<br />He went into denial as he sat there, weeping his guts out, completely<br />oblivious to blazing inferno and the crashing building around him.<br />Suddenly, he felt a jerk and a far voice asking him to get out.<br />Something caught hold of his arm and dragged him away from his<br />father. He didn\'t care what it was, or if he would die. For all he cared<br />his life was already over. He was just looking at his father even when<br />he was being taken away from him. He didn\'t utter a word or resist.<br />It was only when he was out of his former house, and he could see<br />him no more, that he regained his senses. He was on the road<br />outside his house, fallen down and Greg was towering over him.<br />"Are you crazy? The entire building would have fallen on you."<br />exclaimed Greg. Sure enough, pieces of it was already falling down.<br />"Father." said Rhaegon slowly, as if still disbelieving what he had just<br />seen. Greg\'s expression softened, as he realised what had<br />happened.<br />"I am sorry Rhaegon. But your sister is alone. We need to get to her."<br />he said as he slowly placed his hand on his shoulder. A stream of<br />fresh tears made their way down Rhaegon\'s cheeks, as he thought of<br />his little sister. He knew that she couldn\'t handle this news just like<br />he knew that he couldn\'t be the one to break it to her. She always<br />loved her family, and after their mother had died, it was hard to get<br />Aeliana back to her own self, but Rhaegon feared repeating the same<br />feeling was not something she could cope up with.<br />"She\'s so little. She is only sixteen." he cried.<br />"Doesn\'t matter, son. We have to tell it to her. And above all you<br />can\'t be like this in front of her. She is going to be in a state, much<br />worse than you, when she hears this. And you need to be there for<br />her. You are her only family now." he explained. Rhaegon knew that<br />whatever this man had just said was right, but he wasn\'t ready. He<br />thought it was unfair that they had to lose their parents while they<br />were so young. He looked around and saw nothing but corpses, and<br />he thought they were given more justice, than him. They at least will<br />lie in peace with their loved ones forever, not punished to live<br />without them. He wiped the tears off his face, as he braced himself<br />for what was to come. He took a deep breath and got up. His sister<br />needed him, and he would be there for her. He nodded to Greg and<br />slowly they made their way towards Aeliana, who was sitting on a<br />plank of wood away from the fire.<br />* * *<br />She was sitting there, trying to look away from all the fire, but it was<br />difficult in the night. She was getting restless to hear from her<br />brother, and trying very hard to not just get up run towards her<br />house. She knew her brother wouldn\'t like it.<br />Then she saw him. Slowly making his way towards her, with Greg by<br />his side, both had their faces hung low. She could not see her father<br />anywhere near them. She decided to be optimistic here.<br />Maybe he is just injured, to walk all the way till here. she thought, as<br />she got to her feet. She slowly walked towards her brother, who just<br />took her in his arms and hugged her tight. She could hear him crying<br />slowly.<br />"Rhae....what happened?" she mumbled into his ears.<br />"I am sorry Aeliana, I am so sorry." he cried.<br />"No...it can\'t be." she said as she pushed him away harshly. Tears<br />were making down their way on her cheeks as well, as she went into<br />denial.<br />"Listen, okay. I am there for you and I am not leaving you ever, no<br />matter what. We both will always be there for each other." he tried<br />consoling her. She didn\'t say anything as she just ran to her brother<br />and hugged him again. She held him tight as if afraid that he would<br />vanish too.<br />"Shh..." he said slowly into her ears as he made her sit on the ground<br />and he sat down beside her. Both of them were lost in deep<br />thoughts, and slowly before he knew it, exhaustion hit him and<br />Rhaegon went to sleep.<br />* * *<br />Rhaegon woke up to a deep throbbing in his head. He saw his sister,<br />fast asleep, beside him, her face was covered in the dust with certain<br />pattern. A sign that she had cried herself to sleep. It was early in the<br />morning and the sun was just rising. He looked around, all the fire<br />was almost out, which brought him to the harsh reality. He reeled<br />back as the truth hit him. His father was no more. His sister was the<br />only one that he had. Fresh set of tears took its place in his eyes, but<br />he wiped them away. He had to be strong now. He had to be strong<br />for his sister. Suddenly, he realised that, all this while he had not<br />thought of Suzanne. He felt guilt and he stood up in one sudden<br />motion. He had to look for her. She might have made it out and<br />survived the attack. The chances of which were slim but he couldn\'t<br />expect to just give up on her without looking.<br />"OH...You\'re up." Greg smiled. He had come up from behind him.<br />"Suzanne....I have to look for her." he started walking away.<br />"Rhaegon." he called out to him, to stop him. "Listen. Nobody<br />survived okay? As much as I hate to say it, but it is the truth." his<br />expression was grim.<br />"How do you even know that?" he questioned.<br />"What do you think I have been doing the entire night? I have<br />searched through every rubble only to find nothing that yet breaths."<br />he said grimly. Rhaegon didn\'t say anything. In one night he had lost<br />everything that he held dear. "Look, These people didn\'t know what<br />hit them. So, anyone who was in the close proximity of this area is<br />gone. You need to accept that." continued Greg when he didn\'t hear<br />a reply.<br />"But....she..." he couldn\'t complete the sentence as a wave of<br />emotion struck him. He reeled back to their moments together. She<br />had wanted to say something to him, but was interrupted. She was<br />worried and he never would find out, what it was that worried her.<br />He always thought that once they come of age, they would spend<br />the rest of their lives together. But now her life no more existed. She<br />had left him in this world.<br />"But we have to give them proper send off. Cremation. We can\'t<br />just...let them...rot." said Rhaegon wiping the tears off his cheek.<br />"I agree. Although I know that you respected everyone here, but we<br />do not have the resources nor the time to cremate everyone."<br />Rhaegon understood what Greg was implying. And to be honest, he<br />didn\'t care about anyone else at the moment. Just his father and his<br />friend. Although he did not want to accept that he was feeling that<br />way, it was the truth.<br />"Whenever you are ready." Greg said as he walked away.<br />Few minutes later, the three of them were standing around the fresh<br />fire built by them, whose smoke should supposedly be carrying the<br />souls of Weyman Tauworth, Suzanne and Ser Alexon to the land of<br />the dead. Rhaegon stood there trying to make sense of whatever had<br />happened in the past one day, while also trying to keep himself from<br />crying out loud. His sister on the other hand, was weeping<br />uncontrollably and he knew that he had to let her be, give her the<br />time to accept the truth. Greg just stood there expressionless,<br />although Rhaegon knew, he was putting on a hard face just so they<br />could have the liberty to weep. Their lives would never be the same<br />from now on and Rhaegon was trying to deal with it.<br />"If...you are okay, I would like to show you something." said Greg<br />cautiously after what seemed like an hour of just staring blankly in<br />the fire.<br />"What is it?" he was brought back to the present with the sound of<br />his voice. Greg led him away from the cremating grounds and he<br />noticed that Aeliana hadn\'t followed. She was still crying and looking<br />into the fire, as if talking to her father through it. Looking at her like<br />that, it seemed like a bad idea to Greg to leave her alone like that,<br />even for a moment. Rhaegon followed his gaze and said, "She needs<br />her own time, to deal with the truth. It was like that the first time,<br />and I am pretty sure, it is the same now. So if you are worried she<br />will jump into the fire when we are not around or something like<br />that...believe me I know her, she won\'t to such a thing."<br />Greg just gave an awkward pitiful smile.<br />"So what is it?"<br />"When I was looking through the rubble of your house, I found this."<br />he said as he handed him an oval shaped object covered in a black<br />burnt cloth. Rhaegon, dropped the cloth to the ground, to find a<br />scaly object. He didn\'t understand what it was, but by the look on<br />Greg\'s face, he knew that it was something very important.<br />"What is this?" he asked.<br />"That I believe is the reason for, this." he pointed at the ruins of<br />Quencede. Rhaegon just looked at him. "That is a Grimmoth egg. And<br />we all know a Grimmoth protects its own. So what I think is, this egg<br />belongs to the Grimmoth that did this."<br />"I don\'t understand." he shook his head. He had never seen<br />something like this before. And the fact that this was found in his<br />house only made it more confusing. There was no way his father<br />could get his hands on a Grimmoth egg. And he knew that he would<br />have told him if he did.<br />"I am saying, that the Grimmoth was searching for its egg, and when<br />that thing found it, it attacked. And we all have heard stories about<br />how these creatures can detect one another, which might have led it<br />to here."<br />"Then why did it just leave without its egg?" he asked.<br />"That is question that I cannot answer."<br />"But I don\'t understand, how it got here in the first place. My father<br />would never....wait a minute. The Gold Cloaks, Where are they?" he<br />demanded. With all the recent developments, he had forgotten all<br />about them.<br />"How many of them were here?"<br />"Roughly thirty."<br />"I can find none." he said with confidence.<br />"What? That can\'t be possible." he shrugged. "They had camped<br />right outside the village. Near the Shaes."<br />"Yeah, I know. There are footprints in the sand heading away from<br />here."<br />"Son of a Bitch." Rhaegon cursed as he connected the dots. "Their<br />commander, Darius. He lied. He told us that they were on a mission.<br />But what he didn\'t tell us was that, it concerned a Grimmoth egg.<br />Which he didn\'t tell us because-"<br />"-because, if he did then, he knew that we would never have allowed<br />him to camp here." Greg finished the sentence.<br />"And they ran away when the Grimmoth attacked?"<br />"I don\'t think so. I think they got a prior warning and they left before<br />the attack even started." Greg stated.<br />"But why would they do that? Their job is to fight off the<br />Grimmoths."<br />"It is, but their numbers aren\'t enough. They knew they couldn\'t<br />defeat an angry Grimmoth by themselves. So, they saved their lives."<br />"Shit! If they knew, they should have at least warned the others,<br />tried to save as many lives as they could." he spat. Rhaegon\'s anger<br />was cruising. Darius had sold them all out, and that had cost them an<br />entire village and countless lives. He was right all along. He had<br />suspected that man from the moment he saw him, and yet nobody<br />had listened.<br />"But it was their job. And above it all, they caused it. The least they<br />could do was stand and fight, not run and save their own lives." said<br />Rhaegon angrily.<br />"What\'s done is done. We cannot change that. Now we need to<br />decide, what we are going to do next." he said. Greg was clearly<br />making more sense of the whole situation as he was not emotionally<br />involved. Although it was true that, he had lost his home, his<br />property and everything he owned , but considering to what he<br />could have lost, he believed he was lucky to an extent. He also knew<br />that, Tauworth siblings were very vulnerable at the moment and that<br />they needed his help, to get through this tough time.<br />"I know what we are going to do next." said Rhaegon with a serious<br />face. "I am going to find that son of a bitch and burn him alive!"<br />"I do not think that it is a good idea." replied Greg.<br />"I don\'t care what you think!"<br />"Look... I know you are angry and you want revenge. But now is not<br />the time."<br />"Now is exactly the time." he thundered, "I am not going to wait for<br />him show up in front of me, because I know that\'s never going to<br />happen."<br />"It never might, but that doesn\'t mean you go against the Order all<br />alone. You will never succeed." Greg tried to reason with him.<br />"I don\'t care. If I die in the process, I die. I haven\'t got much to live<br />for anyway." he said, "But I am not going to let him get away with all<br />this. He has to pay for what he has done."<br />"Then think about your sister. Are you ready to put her in jeopardy?<br />Because I know for sure, that you two aren\'t going to leave each<br />other now. So whatever decision you make, it will affect her too."<br />"And I want this too." Aeliana said confidently. She had come back,<br />and there was something different about her. It seemed as if she had<br />converted all her grief and fear into anger. There was a<br />determination in her face, the likes of which, Rhaegon had never<br />witnessed before. He knew she had accepted the truth and that she<br />felt angry and alone. This only made him want to do, what he was<br />about to, even more.<br />Greg just looked at the two of them, determined and confident and<br />he knew that there was nothing he could say or do that would get<br />them to drop their idea. So he had to play out his last card in a<br />desperate attempt.<br />"Okay, if you want to do this, you are going to have to do this by<br />yourself, because I do not want to get involved in something like this.<br />My years have come and I am old." he said. He thought, leaving them<br />out to dry would bring some sense to their brains. But he clearly was<br />wrong.<br />"I respect your decision, Greg. You do what you have to. And we will<br />do what we have to." said Rhaegon in a serious tone.<br />"Well I can see there is nothing I can do, to get you off this." Greg<br />gave up.<br />"No, nothing can."<br />"Well in that case, this must be our farewell." he said sadly. Neither<br />of them said anything. Rhaegon looked at Greg and an understanding<br />passed between them, as he nodded.<br />"Well, what are we going to do with this?" asked Greg as he pointed<br />at the Grimmoth egg. Rhaegon thought for a while before he<br />answered.<br />"I am going to keep it." said he.<br />"I am sorry?" asked Aeliana. She couldn\'t believe what her brother<br />was saying. He wanted to keep the one thing, which was the reason<br />that had derailed their entire life.<br />"If you believe that a Grimmoth is going to hatch from that egg and<br />that it will be your pet, you are wrong." said Greg coldly. "That egg is<br />damaged. It was superheated in the fire, and there is no way that, it<br />will hatch."<br />"I am not keeping it because, I want a pet. It is the reason that all this<br />happened, and I would like to keep it as a reminder." Rhaegon<br />sneered.<br />"But wouldn\'t that put a target on our backs?" asked his sister, "I<br />mean, what if it\'s mother comes back for it again?"<br />"If its mother wanted it, it would have taken it. But since it is in my<br />hands right now, I don\'t think it cares anymore."<br />"Fair enough." said Greg and continued after a while, "You two take<br />care of yourselves okay? The rest of Dravieas isn\'t like Quencede.<br />People will betray and break you the second they get the chance to."<br />"We will Greg. Thanks for everything." said Rhaegon as he shook his<br />hand. Greg nodded.<br />"Thank you Greg, for everything you have done for me." said Aeliana<br />tearfully as she hugged her former teacher lightly.<br />"No, Thank you." he said as he held her. "for being my friend."<br />"What are you going to do?" she asked him as they separated.<br />"I don\'t know. But I promise I will figure something out. Don\'t you<br />worry about me. You worry about yourselves, okay? And remember<br />the advise I just gave you. Don\'t trust anyone except for yourselves."<br />he warned.<br />Rhaegon nodded and said, "Good luck, Greg." And then he turned<br />around and walked away from the one place he loved the most, the<br />one place where he had, all his memories from. But he wasn\'t sad,<br />only determined. This incident had changed his life, and his attitude<br />towards it. And so was the same with his sister, who walked beside<br />him, confident to do whatever it took to survive. It was clear from<br />her approach. She wasn\'t sitting in a corner and crying about losing<br />her parents at such young age, as any kid her age would. Instead she<br />was supporting her brother\'s crazy idea of going up against the<br />ancient and one of the most powerful group of people on Dravieas.<br />This whole thing, had toughened them both up, creating a gaping<br />hole in their heart that never would fill, but would be the source of<br />the fuel that drives them. And when Greg saw them both walking<br />away, he didn\'t see, a bunch of kids just wanting revenge. He saw<br />something else in them and he knew that, they would be going to<br />places, achieving things, he never thought possible.<br />"Good luck." he muttered.<br />* * *<br />"He will pay for what he has done. He cannot get away with it." Said<br />Rhaegon who had hidden his face with a cloth tied around his ears.<br />It was moonlight night and there was plenty of light around, making<br />it much harder for them to do what they were about to.<br />"Are you sure you want to do this?" asked his sister Aeliana who was<br />crouched beside him. She had covered her face with a cloth just like<br />her companion in a similar fashion, probably to cover themselves<br />from the dust. There were in the middle of the desert after all and it<br />was a windy night.<br />The location was very bizarre. Right in the middle of nowhere stood a<br />very well guarded fort. No ruler would be foolish enough to stay in<br />this hellish place. There was no sign of anything which could breathe<br />around it, let alone subjects for him to rule. It was as if The Supreme<br />himself didn\'t want this place habited. This place was meant for<br />something else. And the way it was guarded, it was quiet clear that it<br />was very important.<br />"We have come a long way from that dreadful night. We cannot give<br />up now. The way he betrayed us......all of us, that is what has been<br />keeping me up at nights. I want revenge and I shall get it whether<br />you like it or not." he said with a tone that his audience had never<br />heard before. They had indeed come a long way from that dreadful<br />night, in Quencede. Most of the time was spent travelling and<br />plotting. They had come a far too away from home, around six<br />hundred coherts had gotten them to Joretus, only a few days ago.<br />Joretus was a major city in Laekenden. The siblings were taken by<br />surprise when they had seen it for the first time. Its size, its<br />population, everything about it, fascinated them. It was nothing like<br />Quencede. The people here were different. They acted to be your<br />friend only in front of you, but behind you, they would be planning to<br />take from you, all you had. But it still amazed at how different the<br />life was here. It was scary but it was also fun. So when they realised<br />that they had to stay there for a few days just to wait for the right<br />moment. they weren\'t all disappointed. Commander Darius didn\'t<br />like to sit in one place. They had to wait for the moment. And that<br />moment was here. According to what Rhaegon was told, Darius was<br />in this place right now. This was a fort which was about thirty coherts<br />from Joretus, and it belonged to the Order. They had forts like this all<br />over Dravieas. It was their base of operations, and no one other than<br />the Gold Cloaks was allowed inside without invitation. This rule<br />applied not only to the common folk but also to the royalty. But<br />Rhaegon was about to change that as he had decided, that this<br />would be the day that he would finally get his revenge. He had been<br />dreaming about this since that night and he was ready to put<br />everything he had at stake.<br />"I want revenge too." said his sister mildly, "but I don\'t think that<br />killing him is the answer."<br />"What do you mean?"<br />"I mean, we are not killers Rhaegon. Even if we are able to do, what<br />we are about to, and you do kill him, you won\'t be able to live with it<br />for the rest of your life."<br />"But you were ready to do this six months ago." he said. He could not<br />believe he was hearing this from his sister. She was half the reason<br />why he was doing this. And now she did not want to make the<br />person who had ruined their lives, pay.<br />"I said that in the heat of the moment, Rhaegon. I do not want to kill<br />anyone. And I know that deep down you don\'t want to too. You are<br />not that kind of a person." she said slowly, trying to convince her<br />brother from committing an act he surely would regret. "You are<br />angry and you want revenge. I understand that. But all I am asking of<br />you, is to think this through."<br />"You are right Aeliana. Maybe deep down, I don\'t want to kill<br />anyone. But I also need to make him suffer for taking a town off the<br />map." he said angrily. "How do you suggest we do that without<br />killing him?"<br />"By making him realise what he really did." Rhaegon just looked at<br />her as though he didn\'t understand what she was implying. "I am<br />sure, he knows the entire thing is on him, and he lives in denial. And<br />above all, he wasn\'t even there to actually see what really happened.<br />But if he hears it from the people who saw the destruction, who lost<br />everything because of it and if they make him believe it\'s his fault,<br />then he is going to live whatever is left of his life, gloating and<br />cursing himself. He will never be at peace with himself. That is worse<br />than his life ending in a split second."<br />"What makes you think he will even regret what he did?"<br />"Because I know, that if it was any of us, we would."<br />"But he not us, Aeliana." said Rhaegon. "You didn\'t meet this man. I<br />did. He lied to all of us, straight to the face. And that sneer on his<br />face when he got what he wanted...that is not something you see in<br />a man that is capable of regretting."<br />"I don\'t need to see a person to determine whether they will come to<br />terms with what they have done. Because Rhaegon, all of us are the<br />same inside. What we show to others is what the society made us<br />be." she said wisely.<br />Rhaegon thought about what his sister was saying. She was making<br />sense and he knew it. Although he didn\'t like admitting it to himself<br />that even though he was looking forward for this moment, he also<br />feared it. Taking a person\'s life was not easy. His sister had just said<br />out loud, what he was afraid to even think of.<br />"You are right." He said thoughtfully as he nodded. "But I am<br />supposed to be telling you all this, not the other way around. I am<br />the elder one after all."<br />"No." she denied and placed her hand on his shoulder. "It was me<br />who had to tell you this, and that is exactly because you are elder to<br />me. You are elder to me, and that means that you are taking<br />responsibility for me. I know that you are trying hard to do that and<br />you are doing a great job. But under pressure everyone tends to<br />make mistakes and bad decisions which is when we step in and make<br />that right." she smiled.<br />"Look at you, you are all grown up." laughed Rhaegon. He felt proud<br />looking at her. She had taken their father\'s demise better than him.<br />They both knew it.<br />"Well, I better not let you die alone then." she said as she picked up<br />her weapon. "Let\'s get the traitor."</p>', 'Tuesday 20th of December 2017 10:29:15 AM GMT', 45, 2, NULL);
INSERT INTO `bookdetails` (`id`, `uid`, `title`, `descript`, `book`, `dateadd`, `applaud`, `censure`, `articleImage`) VALUES
(2, 'AjayShanbhag', 'Sea Of Monsters', 'The Second Edition Of Percy Jackson, his friend Annabeth Goes missing.', 'CHAPTER 1\n<p>"He will pay for what he has done. He cannot get away with it." Said the man who had hidden his face with a cloth tied around his ears.</p>\r\n<p>It was moonlight night and there was plenty of light around, making it much harder for them to do what they were about to.</p>\r\n<p>"Are you sure you want to do this?" asked the woman who was crouched beside him. She had covered her face with a cloth just like her companion in a similar fashion, probably to cover themselves from the dust. There were in the middle of the desert after all and it was a windy night.</p>\r\n<p>The location was very bizarre. Right in the middle of nowhere stood a very well guarded fort. No ruler would be foolish enough to stay in this hellish place. There was no sign of anything which could breathe around it, let alone subjects for him to rule. It was as if The Supreme himself didn\'t want this place habited. This place was meant for something else. And the way it was guarded, it was quiet clear that it was very important.</p>\r\n<p>"We have come a long way from that dreadful night. We cannot give up now. The way he betrayed us......all of us, that is what has been keeping me up at nights. I want revenge and I shall get it whether you like it or not." he said with a tone that his audience had never heard before.</p>\r\n<p>"Well, I better not let you die alone then." she said as she picked up her weapon. "Let\'s get the traitor."</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em><strong>1</strong></em>.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>"You are going to have to do better than that, if you are to survive in the outside world." said Weyman Tauworth.</p>\r\n<p>Weyman Tauworth was a respected man in the village of Quencede. A master in the art of sword fighting and a well educated person. He was about forty to fifty years old but looked much younger. With dark brown shoulder length hair and sea green eyes, he looked handsome even. He had a well build body and musculature that depicted human\'s perfectness. He looked battle hardened even though he claimed to never have seen a battle in his life. A scar adorned his right arm, and how he got that still remains a mystery to the rest. There was something about him that attracted many towards him. His character was such that many &nbsp;people often referred to him as \'a true noble, unlike those sitting on the throne in Sumterfell.\'&nbsp; He usually helped the local government, govern Quencede. Not that it required much governing. The role of this governing body was just to settle some petty thievery or small land disputes. Things never exceeded this as the people of this village heard, happened everywhere else. Taking someone else\'s life was laughed at here, as a myth. Quencede\'s geographical as well as political position in the map was perfect. It lied on the southern end of the nation Laekenden, and away from its capital Sumterfell. It was also safe from the remaining two nations of Dravieas, Aldhetsern and Oasopern both of which were simply too far from this piece of land. Away from battles, wars, corruption and the politics, not even the Ruler of Laekenden seemed to care much about this place. Surrounded by mountain on one side, and the Barbaric Wilds on the other, with the Ocean of Laekenden lying far down south, it was almost cut off from the rest of Laekenden. It had only one route that allowed people to travel to Joretus, one of the major cities of Laekenden. But even that was quiet a distance away. As a result trade in Quencede was very meagre with traders arriving once in two or three years. But people here did not care. They were self dependent and did not crave for the spices from Aldhetsern or animal meat from Oasopern or fancy clothes from their own nation Laekenden. Simple people just making their living. It seemed as though corruption of mankind had not made its way here yet. Little did they know that it wouldn\'t take long for that to happen.</p>\r\n<p>"I&nbsp; just got a little distracted, nothing to worry about father." said Rhaegon.&nbsp; They were practising the art of sword fighting outside their small house. Rhaegon was Weyman\'s first child and his pride. Rhaegon boasted many of his father\'s features. The same dark brown hairs, sea green eyes and same skin tone. These features were something that characterised the Tauworth\'s. Although their grandfather was a little different but a little shuffling of characteristics wouldn\'t hurt anyone now, would it? Unlike his father, Rhaegon liked to keep his hair of the medium length, never letting it exceed his neck region. More hair meant, he had to spend more time on them, and he was lazy, he couldn\'t afford \'more time\'. Rhaegon\'s muscles were still in the developmental stage, but impressive already which had gotten many young ladies run after him . Above all, he was young and he had his entire life ahead of him, he was nineteen years old after all. The way his routine ran, and with his sword fighting training, it wouldn\'t take him much long to attain his father\'s status. He may be lazy, but when it came to swordsmanship, there was no compromise. He wanted to be the best and the strongest Swordsman ever to walk the lands of Dravieas. And that was what his father was training him to be.</p>\r\n<p>"In a real battle field, there will be fighting raging all around you, swords clashing, people cursing, screaming, dying. Now if you consider your lady friend here a distraction, then in a real battle you wouldn\'t last a minute." he pointed to Suzanne standing aside watching her best friend spar.</p>\r\n<p>Suzanne was a charmer, undoubtedly the most beautiful person Rhaegon had ever seen, which was just a handful bunch considering he had never seen ladies from outside Quencede, a village whose population did not exceed five thousand. Maybe an occasional merchant\'s daughter from Ulharter or Werpost or Joretus. But Suzanne was way better than them all. Suzanne had jet black, long hair. A round face with brown eyes and a perfect shaped nose. Everything about her was beautiful. It was no doubt that many young men lusted after her. But she didn\'t believe in a relationship before marriage. Suzanne and Rhaegon had known each other for almost their entire life. They knew everything about each other, be it a very dark secret or something that everyone knew. They understood and were very much comfortable around each other. There were many who believed that Rhaegon and Suzanne\'s relationship was something more than just best friends. But Rhaegon knew better. And so did Suzanne. Rhaegon respected Suzanne\'s motto of \'no relationship before marriage.\' Although people did freely talk about what a couple they would make and how their marriage will be a celebrated affair. Rhaegon did not mind any of that, in fact he had hoped that he would someday marry her. Suzanne on the other hand had never thought that far. She usually tended to ignore such things. But if she was to be married the very next day, then she knew that she wouldn\'t do it with anyone else other than Rhaegon. But for now they were best friends.</p>\r\n<p>"No, I was just passing by. I will leave now." She said hurriedly as she started walking away, obviously embarrassed. Rhaegon just looked at his feet, he was embarrassed as well.</p>\r\n<p>"I think this is enough for today. Go join her if you like." said his father with a smile on his face. Rhaegon looked up at his father, shocked.</p>\r\n<p>"Father its...not like-" his father cut him off with a raised hand.</p>\r\n<p>"It is okay son. Whatever you are going through.....it happens to the best of us." He almost mused the last part of his statement as if lost in thoughts.</p>\r\n<p>"Are you thinking about how you met mother?" Rhaegon pushed. After all he knew nothing about their history. How they met, or about their marriage, or even his mother\'s death. She had died when he was about six years old. His father had gone into depression for quite a while and even disappeared for some days. But he did return for his children. Rhaegon\'s younger sister, Aeliana who was three years old, was too young to understand the concept of death. She had always sat by the door waiting for her mother until she understood. Rhaegon had a vague image of her face, which was getting blurred every single day. And there was not a single time when he didn\'t probe his father to squeeze more information about her out of him.</p>\r\n<p>"Wait, I think I have changed my decision." joked Weyman.</p>\r\n<p>Rhaegon knew that this chat about his mother would have to wait for another time. His father was a disciplined and serious man, and he only joked rarely. This was definitely one of his best days, and he didn\'t want to ruin it. Besides he was getting an early holiday.</p>\r\n<p>"Sorry father, I am going to go now." laughed Rhaegon as he hurried off after Suzanne.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * * *</p>\r\n<p>Rhaegon had to run quite a distance to catch up with Suzanne.</p>\r\n<p>"You are a fast walker." he said trying to catch his breath.</p>\r\n<p>"Or maybe I was just trying to get away from you." she said without looking at him.</p>\r\n<p>"Well that can\'t be true because if you wanted to, then you wouldn\'t be standing there watching me practise." She didn\'t reply to that.</p>\r\n<p>"Where are you heading to?" he asked.</p>\r\n<p>"Well, I got a bit of a free time so I thought I might just sit on the top of Cleavers hill and clear my mind." Cleavers was a small hill in Quencede, which could easily be climbed in about fifteen minutes. It was famous for its view of Quencede from its top. What with so many people going up there, it almost had, what looked like a natural road with trodden yellow leaves on it marking the way to the top.</p>\r\n<p>"Oh" Rhaegon said, disappointed. Normally when she said she needed to clear her mind, it meant she wanted to be alone.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>"Would you care to join me?" she said, now looking at him. He didn\'t have to answer to that. He just walked beside her and they didn\'t talk until they had reached the top. There was something about her today that seemed new. She was sad, and was deep in thoughts. Rhaegon had sensed it but was just waiting for the right moment, when she would open up herself.</p>\r\n<p>"Nice look from up here, isn\'t it?" he said trying to calm her mood down as they stood on the edge. The entire Quencede, however small it was, was visible from here. The cluster of huts, houses, the market place with people bustling about the streets and a small portion of land on the farther side of the village where Shae - The Outcasts lived. The surrounding mountain chain and the wilds were visible in the distance. It was a breathtaking view that one would never get bored of. The sort, where you can just stand and watch for an entire day, without even feeling a muscle stretch. With all the greenery and the quiet and the peace, it escaped Rhaegon why some people left to stay in the capital Sumterfell. But then again he hadn\'t seen Sumterfell.</p>\r\n<p>"Yes." was all she said. He looked at her, concerned. She was in a deep trance. It was evident from the creases on her forehead and that distant look in her eyes, which didn\'t seem to look at anything in particular. Something was definitely wrong. He still chose not to ask it himself, with the fear that she might withdraw to herself.</p>\r\n<p>"So how is your quest to attain \'all the knowledge there is to attain\', coming along?" he said trying to make conversation.</p>\r\n<p>"It is coming along alright. The Preachers of the Couret seem to know everything. You shouldn\'t have left it you know. They are teaching all sorts of important things now, like why various things in the nature happen and the reasons behind them." she said with a sudden glee in her eyes. Talking about this always made her happy.</p>\r\n<p>Couret was like the Temple in the world of Dravieas. It was also the knowledge hub where all the young had to go until the age of 16 to attain basic knowledge. After that however it was the child\'s choice to whether continue or not. The Preachers were the priests who worshipped The Supreme and his Council of Gods. The Couret existed in every city, town and village no matter how remote it was or which nation it belonged to. Couret was welcome everywhere. It was the only religion in this world after all, one which was followed by everyone.</p>\r\n<p>"Nah, I am alright the way I am. I am a warrior you see. I don\'t want to learn all these stuff and then become a Preacher myself and then sit down and chant The Supreme\'s name all day. And besides I am learning all I can about battle strategies from my father and Ser Alexon. I should be alright. " he said.</p>\r\n<p>She shook her head, "Continuing after the age of sixteen doesn\'t mean that you have to become a Preacher you know? You want to command the army of Laekenden one day, don\'t you? You can be at high places by my way too."</p>\r\n<p>"How is that?"</p>\r\n<p>"Well, you could be the Ruler\'s Advisor."</p>\r\n<p>"Ruler\'s Advisor?" he almost laughed out loud. "That doesn\'t involve any fighting. Commander of the Army is way much better. Is that what you are aiming for anyway? Becoming the Ruler\'s Advisor, and the second most powerful person in Laekenden?"</p>\r\n<p>"No way." she brushed the idea away with disgust. "That involves just too much politics than I can handle."</p>\r\n<p>"So what do you actually want to do? You never seemed to have shared that one."</p>\r\n<p>"Well....." her momentary glee seemed to have vanished as the sadness took their place back on her face.</p>\r\n<p>"Is there something wrong Suzanne?" he asked her finally. His attempt to make her mood light had only worked for a moment. Now he was concerned about her. He had never seen this kind of behaviour from her before. She looked at him, deep inside his eyes, deciding whether to reveal her secret or not.</p>\r\n<p>Rhaegon watched into her eyes as tears were slowly filling in them like a flood in a village. He gave her a reassuring smile and laid his hand on her shoulder. And in an instant she made the decision. She could trust Rhaegon. She had to reveal this to someone and who better than to than her own best friend. In the few hours that she had learnt the secret, she was unable to think clearly. She had to get it out, which is why she had headed to Rhaegon\'s place instinctively, hoping to talk to him about what she had been told. Whether to believe it or not.</p>\r\n<p>"Rhaegon.......its" she broke down unable to control herself. He just pulled her close and hugged her, the way they always did when either of them was depressed.</p>\r\n<p>"Rhaegon....its.....wait, what is that?" she suddenly said in a shocked tone as she gently pulled away from his embrace. Rhaegon looked in the direction she was pointing at. It seemed as if a large sand storm was heading toward Quencede. It wasn\'t very far from the village.</p>\r\n<p>"What in the name of The Supreme is that?" he strained his eyes to see clearly. And that is when he realised that it was not a sand storm. It was just the sand displaced from the marching of a large number of people. It was an army battalion.</p>\r\n<p>An army at Quencede was unthinkable. It didn\'t make sense. This wasn\'t a trade hub or near the borders to attract such interest. Unless the entire Laekenden had been defeated and the conquerors had come to claim their last prize at the edge of Dravieas, this was just insane. And even if that was the case, nobody would have needed an army to take on Quencede. There would be almost no resistance here, there were obviously no soldiers of Laekenden here, just some young fighters and that too their numbers not exceeding ten.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>"It is not Laekenden." he said almost to himself.</p>\r\n<p>"What?" asked a startled Suzanne.</p>\r\n<p>"That is definitely not the army of Laekenden. Laekenden military wears blue coloured cloaks. So unless they have decided to change banners, that is not Laekenden." he explained. The unknown army was almost upon their village, when they got a clear look at them. About fifty men in Golden coloured armours, seemed to be marching towards their village. Although they had no weapons drawn or the stance of an army which was almost upon their prey, they were a fearful sight.</p>\r\n<p>"They are Gold Cloaks." said Suzanne, shocked.</p>\r\n<p>"The Order of Denkerst?" he asked, with certain amount of awe in his voice. "What could they be possibly doing in Quencede?" he asked. And in return she just gave him a concerned look.</p>\r\n<p>"This is not good." he said, "come on we have to warn the others."</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;* * * &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"Are you sure they were Gold Cloaks?" asked his father, suddenly standing up from his chair. He was shocked to his bones. They were in his hut. Rhaegon and Suzanne had ran as fast as they could to warn the rest of them, and to raise some defence if it was even possible.</p>\r\n<p>"Yes, Ser Weyman. I myself saw it from atop Cleavers with Rhaegon. I have studied about the Order of Denkerst, that battalion\'s formation matches one of the most common Order\'s formation. And besides their armour style clearly says it all." Suzanne said who had recovered from the emotional breakdown she had just had. In this moment of crisis she had forgotten all about her secret and its possible implications. It had to wait for another time.</p>\r\n<p>"Well, let us not keep them waiting then." said Weyman as he picked up his sword which was kept on a rack.</p>\r\n<p>"Shouldn\'t we call on the others and try to defend it?" asked Rhaegon.</p>\r\n<p>"We should call on the others, but I don\'t think that this place needs defending at the moment." said his father calmly.</p>\r\n<p>"What do you mean?" Rhaegon was confused. He didn\'t care if it was the Gold Cloaks or a bunch of thieves, in his books, if a group of armed people are heading directly towards you, then it obviously meant trouble. It had failed him why his father didn\'t see it that way.</p>\r\n<p>"If what Suzanne said is true, if they really are the Golden Cloaks, then we have nothing to worry about. The Gold cloaks do not burn down cities. They do not exist to fight the humans. And they certainly do not have any political ambitions. And until they do we have nothing to worry about. Now, Suzanne go warn the other members of the local council. And Rhaegon you come with me, let us go welcome them." he commanded and Rhaegon knew that, this was the end of the discussion. Still he was uneasy, there was something that he felt was not right. Now this might be his intuition or him just being a little too pessimistic. Rhaegon picked up his sword as well and headed out the house after his father and Suzanne.</p>\r\n<p>"Take care Rhaegon." she said slowly after which she ran off in the other direction, towards the heart of the village. Meanwhile him and his father were heading towards the outer village, the part where the Shae lived. No doubt they would be panicking right now.</p>\r\n<p>"Don\'t be scared, the worst that could happen is that we all get killed, warriors death and the rest who are alive get to serve the new masters." said Weyman with some amount of amusement in his voice. They were now walking with a brisk pace down the village lane. They could already hear the thumps of the battalion\'s marching.</p>\r\n<p>"What? I am not scared. I don\'t care what happens to me. I am just being cautious about what might happen." &nbsp;said a shocked Rhaegon. He couldn\'t believe that his father thought that he was scared. Whereas the truth was that, he wasn\'t feeling anything at all except adrenaline rushing into his blood and the surge of excitement. He wasn\'t scared at all. This worried him the most. Any person would have been shivering at their current prospect. It was just two of them going to meet a battalion of well trained soldiers. Even if what his father had told about the Gold Cloaks was true, it didn\'t mean that they were safe. If anything went wrong, it would mean that it would be just the two of them against around fifty battle hardened soldiers. And they didn\'t have any considerable backup too. Yet, with even these odds, he wasn\'t at all frightened.</p>\r\n<p>"I know. I was just joking." laughed his father. Rhaegon looked at him suspiciously. There was something seriously wrong here. His \'disciplined\' father was joking even at times like this?</p>\r\n<p>"What has happened to you?"</p>\r\n<p>"What? I am being a little optimistic here okay? And it feels good, you should try it sometimes." smiled his father, only to be returned by his son\'s glare. "Come on, you don\'t really think they are going to attack Quencede do you? They are Gold Cloaks and they keep track of each and every place. They would know that we have no defence and yet they would still bring a battalion? I don\'t think so. I believe that whatever is going to happen, it will be for our own good."</p>\r\n<p>Rhaegon realised that whatever his father was saying, was actually making sense. He smiled at his father.</p>\r\n<p>"Look, I know that you feel, none of this is right. And you are correct at your place to some extent. We will take on whatever is coming, together. Relax a little." said his father. Rhaegon nodded his assent.</p>\r\n<p>They had arrived at the village\'s outer part. The Shae\'s were definitely getting restless as they looked as if they were ready to burst into the inner village. There were men arguing about reasons unknown but the women and children did their best to stay in the shadow and keep their mouths shut. The golden army was visible at a distance now, lead by a single person on horseback, valiantly riding at a slow pace so that his foot soldiers behind him could keep up.</p>\r\n<p>Ser Alexon had already arrived at the scene before Rhaegon and his father. He was just standing there with a sheathed sword strapped to his waist, watching the golden army arrive, whilst completely ignoring the shouting Shae\'s all around him. He was a different person. A war veteran and the former commander of a Laekenden battalion. And his battalion was one among many that fought against the Duncan Stormwell\'s army and he had a major role in defeating Stormwell and putting Galer Redmere at the throne of Laekenden. However, he was injured considerably, with his left arm paralysed, during the war and he quit shortly after, seeing that he could not serve the throne the way he previously did. However many people said that, he had seen many horrors in that war that he could take it no more and he receded to this outlandish place for his retirement. His father and Ser Alexon were friends since then. Ser Alexon might have a paralysed hand but he was still a fearful sight in a direct combat. His physique was built for war. He had a major role in Rhaegon\'s sword fighting training.</p>\r\n<p>"Welcome to the party, Weyman." Ser Alexon said as he saw them arrive.</p>\r\n<p>"We should probably ask the Shae\'s to leave. They will only make things worse." said Weyman. Ser Alexon just nodded in return. He was just as moody as Rhaegon\'s father was.</p>\r\n<p>Weyman turned around and shouted as loud as he possibly could, addressing the hundreds of Shaes there. "Listen everyone, the women and the children are allowed to enter Quencede until further decision is made. You can ask for the villagers to give you shelter and I am sure that they will be more than willing to help at times like this. The men however are advised to go back to their huts as we cannot accommodate everyone. You are to await further announcements. In case things get out of hand, run into the village and save your family and in the process, if possible try and help others."</p>\r\n<p>After the announcement, some gave out wails of disappointment while others, bid their good byes to their children and wives and prepared to head into village. The entire community burst into action, getting ready to do whatever it was that they were advised to do.</p>\r\n<p>The code of Dravieas had termed the low borns as \'The Shae\'. They were never allowed to enter any village or city or anything without any purpose. Purpose being, work. It was these people after all who were the labour force. They did everything from cleaning houses to cook to labour in building massive structures under the supervision of a high born. The only place they were allowed to however was ironically, the Couret. The Couret\'s were usually located at the heart of the cities and villages, which made the Shaes not to go there as well. These poor souls stayed in camps outside cities and villages. They would get their supplies from the governing body separately at a slight higher cost. Rhaegon hated it all. He had never understood the concept of \'low borns and high borns\'. When questioned, some would say to leave things as they are and some would look down upon him as if he had done a crime. His father however agreed with him, but not to an extreme extent. He commanded much respect in this village, yet he had never publicly raised this subject. But he knew that, his father couldn\'t achieve anything in this prospect. This was a practise that was going on since time immemorial and was followed everywhere in Dravieas. It would take more than just one man to bring about a change. If it was in Rhaegon\'s power, he would declare every Low born to be a high born and thus abolish the practise. Sadly, he knew that this was not going to be true, at least in the present scenario.</p>\r\n<p>"The Council won\'t like that." said Ser Alexon, still looking straight at the marching army.</p>\r\n<p>"I know. To hell with the Council. They really won\'t care about where the Shae\'s are at times like this." he said little angrily.</p>\r\n<p>"You really don\'t know them then." he said, now turning to look straight into Weyman\'s eyes. "They do not look down upon the Shae\'s as softy as we do. What do you say Rhaegon?"</p>\r\n<p>"Well.....I was about to ask, why you didn\'t let the men enter too. I mean they will be more safer inside the village even if they are sitting on roads." he said little hesitantly.</p>\r\n<p>This statement brought smiles onto both old men\'s faces.</p>\r\n<p>"Like father like son I believe." chuckled Ser Alexon.</p>\r\n<p>"Hurry up people." commanded Weyman as the army had almost arrived.</p>', 'Tuesday 25th of December 2017 10:29:15 AM GMT', 7, 0, NULL),
(4, 'JasonChase', 'Percy Jackson', 'Annabeth Loves Percy with all her heart and feet.', 'CHAPTER 1\n<p>"Don\'t be scared, the worst that could happen is that we all get killed, warriors death and the rest who are alive get to serve the new masters." said Weyman with some amount of amusement in his voice. They were now walking with a brisk pace down the village lane. They could already hear the thumps of the battalion\'s marching.</p>\r\n<p>"What? I am not scared. I don\'t care what happens to me. I am just being cautious about what might happen." &nbsp;said a shocked Rhaegon. He couldn\'t believe that his father thought that he was scared. Whereas the truth was that, he wasn\'t feeling anything at all except adrenaline rushing into his blood and the surge of excitement. He wasn\'t scared at all. This worried him the most. Any person would have been shivering at their current prospect. It was just two of them going to meet a battalion of well trained soldiers. Even if what his father had told about the Gold Cloaks was true, it didn\'t mean that they were safe. If anything went wrong, it would mean that it would be just the two of them against around fifty battle hardened soldiers. And they didn\'t have any considerable backup too. Yet, with even these odds, he wasn\'t at all frightened.</p>\r\n<p>"I know. I was just joking." laughed his father. Rhaegon looked at him suspiciously. There was something seriously wrong here. His \'disciplined\' father was joking even at times like this?</p>\r\n<p>"What has happened to you?"</p>\r\n<p>"What? I am being a little optimistic here okay? And it feels good, you should try it sometimes." smiled his father, only to be returned by his son\'s glare. "Come on, you don\'t really think they are going to attack Quencede do you? They are Gold Cloaks and they keep track of each and every place. They would know that we have no defence and yet they would still bring a battalion? I don\'t think so. I believe that whatever is going to happen, it will be for our own good."</p>\r\n<p>Rhaegon realised that whatever his father was saying, was actually making sense. He smiled at his father.</p>\r\n<p>"Look, I know that you feel, none of this is right. And you are correct at your place to some extent. We will take on whatever is coming, together. Relax a little." said his father. Rhaegon nodded his assent.</p>\r\n<p>They had arrived at the village\'s outer part. The Shae\'s were definitely getting restless as they looked as if they were ready to burst into the inner village. There were men arguing about reasons unknown but the women and children did their best to stay in the shadow and keep their mouths shut. The golden army was visible at a distance now, lead by a single person on horseback, valiantly riding at a slow pace so that his foot soldiers behind him could keep up.</p>\r\n<p>Ser Alexon had already arrived at the scene before Rhaegon and his father. He was just standing there with a sheathed sword strapped to his waist, watching the golden army arrive, whilst completely ignoring the shouting Shae\'s all around him. He was a different person. A war veteran and the former commander of a Laekenden battalion. And his battalion was one among many that fought against the Duncan Stormwell\'s army and he had a major role in defeating Stormwell and putting Galer Redmere at the throne of Laekenden. However, he was injured considerably, with his left arm paralysed, during the war and he quit shortly after, seeing that he could not serve the throne the way he previously did. However many people said that, he had seen many horrors in that war that he could take it no more and he receded to this outlandish place for his retirement. His father and Ser Alexon were friends since then. Ser Alexon might have a paralysed hand but he was still a fearful sight in a direct combat. His physique was built for war. He had a major role in Rhaegon\'s sword fighting training.</p>\r\n<p>"Welcome to the party, Weyman." Ser Alexon said as he saw them arrive.</p>\r\n<p>"We should probably ask the Shae\'s to leave. They will only make things worse." said Weyman. Ser Alexon just nodded in return. He was just as moody as Rhaegon\'s father was.</p>\r\n<p>Weyman turned around and shouted as loud as he possibly could, addressing the hundreds of Shaes there. "Listen everyone, the women and the children are allowed to enter Quencede until further decision is made. You can ask for the villagers to give you shelter and I am sure that they will be more than willing to help at times like this. The men however are advised to go back to their huts as we cannot accommodate everyone. You are to await further announcements. In case things get out of hand, run into the village and save your family and in the process, if possible try and help others."</p>\r\n<p>After the announcement, some gave out wails of disappointment while others, bid their good byes to their children and wives and prepared to head into village. The entire community burst into action, getting ready to do whatever it was that they were advised to do.</p>\r\n<p>The code of Dravieas had termed the low borns as \'The Shae\'. They were never allowed to enter any village or city or anything without any purpose. Purpose being, work. It was these people after all who were the labour force. They did everything from cleaning houses to cook to labour in building massive structures under the supervision of a high born. The only place they were allowed to however was ironically, the Couret. The Couret\'s were usually located at the heart of the cities and villages, which made the Shaes not to go there as well. These poor souls stayed in camps outside cities and villages. They would get their supplies from the governing body separately at a slight higher cost. Rhaegon hated it all. He had never understood the concept of \'low borns and high borns\'. When questioned, some would say to leave things as they are and some would look down upon him as if he had done a crime. His father however agreed with him, but not to an extreme extent. He commanded much respect in this village, yet he had never publicly raised this subject. But he knew that, his father couldn\'t achieve anything in this prospect. This was a practise that was going on since time immemorial and was followed everywhere in Dravieas. It would take more than just one man to bring about a change. If it was in Rhaegon\'s power, he would declare every Low born to be a high born and thus abolish the practise. Sadly, he knew that this was not going to be true, at least in the present scenario.</p>\r\n<p>"The Council won\'t like that." said Ser Alexon, still looking straight at the marching army.</p>\r\n<p>"I know. To hell with the Council. They really won\'t care about where the Shae\'s are at times like this." he said little angrily.</p>\r\n<p>"You really don\'t know them then." he said, now turning to look straight into Weyman\'s eyes. "They do not look down upon the Shae\'s as softy as we do. What do you say Rhaegon?"</p>\r\n<p>"Well.....I was about to ask, why you didn\'t let the men enter too. I mean they will be more safer inside the village even if they are sitting on roads." he said little hesitantly.</p>\r\n<p>This statement brought smiles onto both old men\'s faces.</p>\r\n<p>"Like father like son I believe." chuckled Ser Alexon.</p>\r\n<p>"Hurry up people." commanded Weyman as the army had almost arrived.</p>\r\n<p>Rhaegon, his father and Ser Alexon stood together facing the army. Strangely, he was the only one, having his hand on the hilt. The Golden army had come to halt right in front of them. Rhaegon looked behind him, the entire Shae\'s camp had gone silent. The women and children had already made their way into the village. Most of the men were inside their huts, with some curious eyes peering from the windows and some brave men watching right from the outside. He turned to face the guests. All he saw was beaten and bloodied soldiers, led by a burly man sitting on a horse. They were Gold Cloaks alright. It was crystal clear now that he could see them all up close.</p>\r\n<p>"Greetings!" said the man on the horse, bending his back a little, a gesture of respect. His voice was very coarse and heavy.</p>\r\n<p>"Greetings to you too, commander!" his father greeted back.</p>\r\n<p>The commander looked behind them and realised what had happened. "Oh, you didn\'t think we were invaders now, did you?" he smiled.</p>\r\n<p>"What is the Order doing here?" asked Ser Alexon suspiciously. The commander looked quiet shocked with Ser Alexon\'s tone.</p>\r\n<p>"So right to the point, huh?" he said as he climbed down from his horse, and quickly a soldier ran forward to hold its reins. The commander was a tall man even when he was not on the horse. "No matter. We are the Order of Denkerst." he took off his helmet, revealing a crooked and scared face. He had a bloodshot eyes and a scar running through his nose, and his lips were as thin as a thread. An ugly man to be honest. "And I am Darius, the commander of 3rd battalion of the Order." he said proudly.</p>\r\n<p>"And I am Alexon, former Commander of a Laekenden battalion."</p>\r\n<p>"Oh! That explains." he smiled.</p>\r\n<p>"So what do we owe this pleasure?" asked Rhaegon\'s father.</p>\r\n<p>Darius hesitated for a moment before he spoke. "Umm..... we are in the middle of a mission, assigned to us by the Welminer himself. And we are looking to camp here to rest and refill our supplies, before we head out to our final destination."</p>\r\n<p>By now, the governing body of the village had arrived. All elderly people looking worried and a little angry, probably because of the little Shae matter. All the Shaes that were in the camp, came out to watch the whole scene as they realised that there was going to be no bloodshed and that they were all safe.</p>\r\n<p>"But that doesn\'t explain the blood."&nbsp; Rhaegon said. He had observed the blood that was on all of their armours.</p>\r\n<p>"Excuse me?" asked a shocked Darius.</p>\r\n<p>All eyes were boring into Rhaegon now. "The blood stains on your armour," he said pointing at their them, "They look fresh. Probably two or three days old. So who did you have to fight on your way here?"</p>\r\n<p>"Sorry, who are you again?" said the commander as he made an absent minded attempt to wipe his cloak clean.</p>\r\n<p>"Rhaegon Tauworth."</p>\r\n<p>"See Rhaegon, these blood stains are not of a human being as you might suspect. These are some of the wild wolves that we have had to encounter in the wilds."</p>\r\n<p>"With all due respect Commander, how many men did you actually set out with?" he asked.</p>\r\n<p>"What do you mean by that?" asked back the commander, now getting a little annoyed.</p>\r\n<p>"Your battalion here houses thirty three men, give or take a few. Nobody takes such a odd number into any mission. So unless, you lost a few men along the way, which would be impossible if wild wolves were the only things that you faced, it doesn\'t make sense. So would you care to explain, what actually happened?" This whole thing was very suspicious to him. He didn\'t believe a single word the commander said. Something was definitely wrong here.</p>\r\n<p>"Careful there child." said an angered Darius.</p>\r\n<p>"Enough!" said the village leader. "All they want to do is camp here right? I can see no harm in this. Commander Darius, you can have your men camp here and you are welcome to my house as a guest."</p>\r\n<p>"But-" Rhaegon\'s protest was cut short by, the village leader.</p>\r\n<p>"I appreciate your readiness to act son, but I think we got things in control here."</p>\r\n<p>Rhaegon pulled back after this. It seemed nobody was seeing this the way he was seeing it. There was nothing he could do now except watch Darius\' smug smile, as he pushed through him to make his way to the village headman\'s house.</p>\r\n<p>"Camp here! Raise tents. Provisions will be taken care of shortly." announced Darius. After which he headed into the village to the leader\'s house. The crowd slowly began dissipating.</p>\r\n<p>"Nice work there." appreciated Ser Alexon, as soon as they were alone. &nbsp;"It takes courage to speak up like that and that too, to such an audience."</p>\r\n<p>"Thanks, Ser." he smiled.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;"There is this feeling that I have......that something is not right." Rhaegon continued.</p>\r\n<p>"You are right, Rhaegon. We have got to keep our eyes open." he replied as he too headed off into the village.</p>\r\n<p>"Come on, we have got work to do." said Weyman as he directed his son to follow him into the village. "As much as you may argue, we have to send the Shaes back or else the council would burn me alive." They both laughed.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; * * *</p>', 'Tuesday 10th of January 2017 10:29:15 AM GMT', 2, NULL, NULL),
